'}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2013-12-02 14:52:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 24: Do not merge

Can't break backwards compat.  Please do not ignore this review comment.

Instead, provide (a) new plugin(s) with the behavior that you want, and I will remove the -2.

It doesn't matter what the spec says, as it is up to the end user to determine how to process that:  it might well be the user@domain is the REMOTE_USER username, but namespace is implicit in there;  that is not the the way that the backend needs to store it, and so we are not violating the spec.  Keystone is just performing its own logic beyond that."}, {'account_id': 91, 'date': '2013-12-02 18:37:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 24:

> Can't break backwards compat. Please do not ignore this
> review comment.

I am not ignoring it, I am just pointing out that compatibility has been
already broken from V2 to V3 API. And it was broken between two V3 API
releases (Grizzly and Havana). Any plugin that was working in V2 is not
working in V3. Any plugin working in Grizzly V3 would not working in Havana
V3.

> Instead, provide (a) new plugin(s) with the behavior that you want, and I will remove
> the -2.

I am not refusing to submit that, but I want to reach consensus first.

> It doesn't matter what the spec says, as it is up to the end user to determine how to 
> process that: it might well be the user@domain is the REMOTE_USER username, but 
> namespace is implicit in there; that is not the the way that the backend needs to 
> store it, and so we are not violating the spec. Keystone is just performing its own 
> logic beyond that.

I disagree with you here. First of all, it is not documented anywhere that
REMOTE_USER must be formatted as "username@domain", so I as an operator infer
that this should be following the WSGI semantics.

Secondly, you are assuming that the part coming after the "@"
always means a different namespace, but this is not always true. I can perfectly have
"john@foo.com" and "john@bar.com" under the same domain and tenant, being both 
authenticated by the same external authentication system (think for example on
an inter-organization collaboration, not uncommon in the scientific
computing).

Moreover, from a resource provider point of view, now I need to reconfigure what was
working with V2 external authentication to make it work with V3, and in some
cases I won't be able to make both work at the same time. If I was using
external authentication based on emails and I do not want to use domains at all,
it is simply broken. My users will differ if using V2 and V3. This is also
true when external authentication is not based on emails, BUT the username can
contain an "@": it is broken.

This leads to a mess form an operator point of view. See
https://bugs.launchpad.net/keystone/+bug/1253484 as an example. Add to that
bug report the usage of several external authentication methods and it renders
into a configuration mess.'}, {'account_id': 6486, 'date': '2013-12-03 01:05:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 24:

[{'created': '2013-10-08 14:11:03.000000000', 'message': 'Do not split REMOTE_USER by "@" in ExternalDefault

When using external authentication the current code splits the
REMOTE_USER variable by the "@". This is ok if we are using domains
(i.e. keystone.auth.plugins.external.ExternalDomain) since any WSGI
middleware must append the domain to the username. However, if we are
using ExternalDefault the code also splits the domain by the "@",
even though there should be no domain there. ExternalDefault should
not split the username at all even if it contains an "@".

Partial-Bug: #1211233
DocImpact: document this behaviour in the external modules documentation

'}, {'created': '2013-11-27 17:17:12.000000000', 'message': 'Fix external auth (REMOTE_USER) plugin support

According to the WSGI specification "REMOTE_USER should be the string
username of the user, nothing more" [1], therefore no modifications
should be made to the REMOTE_USER variable and it should be fully
considered as the username. Otherwise the expected semantics of the
REMOTE_USER variable change, and an site administrator could get
undesirable side-effects.

[1] http://wsgi.readthedocs.org/en/latest/specifications/simple_authentication.html#specification

In external.Default, we cannot split REMOTE_USER by "@". This split
will cause errors for remote users containing an "@" (not only
emails, but also X.509 subjects, etc).

In external.Domain we should not split also the REMOTE_USER by "@". A
new environment variable (REMOTE_DOMAIN) is introduced, so that any
external plugin can pass down the right domain for the user.

Closes-Bug: #1211233
Closes-Bug: #1253484

DocImpact: Document the two plugins. Reflect the semantics of
the REMOTE_USER variable for the WSGI filters. Backwards compatibility
will be broken with this change.

Change-Id: I1b2521a526fa976146dfe2fcf4d4c1851416d8ae
'}, {'created': '2013-12-04 14:51:28.000000000', 'message': 'Fix external auth (REMOTE_USER) plugin support

According to the WSGI specification "REMOTE_USER should be the string
username of the user, nothing more" [1], therefore no modifications
should be made to the REMOTE_USER variable and it should be fully
considered as the username. Otherwise the expected semantics of the
REMOTE_USER variable change, and an site administrator could get
undesirable side-effects.

[1] http://wsgi.readthedocs.org/en/latest/specifications/simple_authentication.html#specification

In external.Default, we cannot split REMOTE_USER by "@". This split
will cause errors for remote users containing an "@" (not only
emails, but also X.509 subjects, etc).

In external.Domain we should not split also the REMOTE_USER by "@". A
new environment variable (REMOTE_DOMAIN) is introduced, so that any
external plugin can pass down the right domain for the user.

Two legacy plugins are also provided with the same behaviour as the
Havana shipped ones.

Closes-Bug: #1211233
Closes-Bug: #1253484

DocImpact: Document the new and legacy plugins. Reflect the semantics of
the REMOTE_USER variable for the WSGI filters. The default external
authentication plugin has been changed.

Change-Id: I1b2521a526fa976146dfe2fcf4d4c1851416d8ae

commit_message:
Fix external auth (REMOTE_USER) plugin support

According to the WSGI specification "REMOTE_USER should be the string
username of the user, nothing more" [1], therefore no modifications
should be made to the REMOTE_USER variable and it should be fully
considered as the username. Otherwise the expected semantics of the
REMOTE_USER variable change, and an site administrator could get
undesirable side-effects.

[1] http://wsgi.readthedocs.org/en/latest/specifications/simple_authentication.html#specification

Moreover, it is important to have a consistent behaviour regarding
external authentication in V2 (not domain aware), V3 with default
domain and V3 with domain (see Bug #1253484) so that we produce similar
results with the three methods.

This change aims to solve this issues by removing the split of the
REMOTE_USER variable by "@" at all:

- In external.DefaultDomain, we cannot split REMOTE_USER by "@". This split
  will cause errors for remote users containing an "@" (not only
  emails, but also X.509 subjects, etc). The external.DefaultDomain plugin
  considers the REMOTE_USER variable as the username, and the configured
  default domain as the domain

- In external.Domain we should not split also the REMOTE_USER by "@". A
  new environment variable (REMOTE_DOMAIN) is introduced, so that any
  external plugin can pass down the right domain for the user. The
  external.Domain plugin considers the REMOTE_USER as the username, the
  REMOTE_DOMAIN as the domain if it is present, otherwise it takes the
  configured default domain.

- Two legacy plugins are also provided with the same behaviour as the
  Havana shipped ones. This plugins should not be used and are provided
  for compatibility reasons (see Bug #1254619)

Closes-Bug: #1254619
Closes-Bug: #1211233
Closes-Bug: #1253484

DocImpact: This change breaks backwards compatibility in favour of
security (see bug #1254619), therefore an upgrade not is needed. It is
needed to document the new plugins and state clearly the semantics of
the REMOTE_USER and REMOTE_DOMAIN variable for the WSGI filters. The
default external authentication plugin has been changed from
exernal.ExternalDefault to external.Default.

Change-Id: I1b2521a526fa976146dfe2fcf4d4c1851416d8ae

I also noticed this recently, it seems to happen at the part where the access token is exchanged for a keystone token. but this change doesn't seem to add any new logic, just removes some of the optional dependency work"}, {'account_id': 7706, 'date': '2014-01-02 09:03:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

You are right, this patch doesn't add any new logic, it fixes existing. When we clear _future_optionals, there is no way to tell where some optional component is referenced (oauth in our case). And when this component will become available, there is no way to update objects that were referencing this component. I think this bug caused by inattentive copy/paste of code that process regular dependencies.
That's why (I think) someone added service.load_backends(include_oauth1=True) to tests and code that load oauth extension in load_backends function when include_oauth1 is true. But that thing only fixed tests, not application."}, {'account_id': 7706, 'date': '2014-01-02 09:24:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Here are two commits that caused this problem:
https://github.com/openstack/keystone/commit/5e04343ff5b5f6f7ac896492ebdb4f992d07be47
https://github.com/openstack/keystone/commit/acd70e5641a81f9e0333dfc495ac38cadaa450df'}, {'account_id': 6486, 'date': '2014-01-02 19:27:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(2 inline comments)

I think the problem is that the oauth backend is loaded after we've already called dependency.resolve_future_dependencies() .

The oauth backend probably isn't loaded until the paste pipeline is loaded.

If you look at keystone-all[1], 
resolve_future_dependencies is called from service.load_backends() at line 129, but the paste stuff isn't done until 132.

So I think the correct fix is to move dependency.resolve_future_dependencies() out of load_backends() and put it after line 139 in keystone-all.

This change will have to be made in the other places where load_backends() happens (the http server for example).

[1] http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/keystone/tree/bin/keystone-all?id=ce5fcb13c5fec5de3eeab58453713a061e40168a#n129"}, {'account_id': 6486, 'date': '2014-01-02 19:28:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: (1 inline comment)

'}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2014-01-02 22:45:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Do not merge

Not true that the value is always None:  the oauth code should get initialized when the pipeline processes it, which will be at application load time.'}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2014-01-04 03:17:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

"}, {'account_id': 6482, 'date': '2014-01-06 22:44:17.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 6482, 'date': '2014-01-06 22:45:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Anton,

Can you please try this patch? It should load oauth properly (after the pipeline is loaded).'}, {'account_id': 6486, 'date': '2014-01-06 22:48:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Doesn't tests have to be changed, too? it calls load_backends."}, {'account_id': 6482, 'date': '2014-01-06 23:07:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

It's already calling out to load oauth specifically here: https://github.com/openstack/keystone/blob/master/keystone/tests/core.py#L352 

And the error wasn't being caught from the tests anyway, 'we don't have unit tests that reflect how the server actually starts'"}, {'account_id': 6486, 'date': '2014-01-06 23:12:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Steve - load_backends used to do dependency.resolve_future_dependencies() , which it doesn't do now. So after calling load_backends ( https://github.com/openstack/keystone/blob/master/keystone/tests/core.py#L352 ) the tests should do "dependency.resolve_future_dependencies()".

Also, I think it would make more sense now to remove the include_oauth1 option from load_backends and move that into tests load_backends (right after https://github.com/openstack/keystone/blob/master/keystone/tests/core.py#L352 ).

This would make the tests closer to how the server actually start up.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-01-07 01:21:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Works for me

commit_message:
Resolve oauth dependency after paste pipeline is loaded

When trying to authenticate with the oauth plugin, it is
possible that the dependency is not yet loaded, and as a result
the user will receive an error message: "Oauth is disabled"

This patch will ensure the dependency is loaded after the pipeline

Fixes: bug #1264803

Change-Id: I37484bf844896b1a1b560923a8afaf99e91635e4

commit_message:
Deprecate/remove scheduler select_hosts()

This call is no longer used and can be removed from the scheduler api and
drivers. For backwards compatibility, the existing manager method is kept
but instead call driver.select_destinations() and convert the result to
the old format.

Conductor manager, as the last user of this call, used it to select
a target for live migration, but now instead makes calls to
select_destinations() to get the same information. The related change
to conductor manager is here: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/52311/

Change-Id: I702515a086e7f33c48fa9ee106271c868b660540

commit_message:
Add a flexible API version choice for Cinder, Glance and Heat

The version of the authentication url is set to v1.0 for some
projects by default. We can make it configurable via the parameter
"$IDENTITY_API_VERSION".

Closes-Bug: #1253539
Change-Id: I6640e345d1317b1308403c95b13f8a998320241b

commit_message:
Switch rally.sshutils from 'eventlet' to 'time'

Inasmuch as tests.test_sshutils.SSHTestCase.test_wait and
test_wait_timeout fail on py26 on Mac OS, it was decided to remove
'eventlet' from sshutils and instead of it use 'time' module and it's
same functions.

Change-Id: I7d0ae176b0419e09157c09d7c6213edc109df2e0
Closes-Bug: #1264403

commit_message:
Add missing license header to test file

All the other tests have license headers, so this one should too.

I picked 2013 for the copyright year because that's when "git log"
says it was first and last touched.

commit_message:
Fix for parsing error with Dollar Sign ($) in values

Python String template uses '$$' as an escape when a '$' is required
in the value. So add a test case to make sure that works.

Many users end up trying a backslash to escape as well, let's add
support and a test case for that as well

DocImpact

Change-Id: I403cc98505a95f633b5f29ba8f819a2e9c7d58a6
Closes-Bug: #1259729

commit_message:
libvirt: stop overwriting LibvirtConfigCPU in get_host_capabilities

Currently, LibvirtConfigCPU configuration is being overwritten with baselineCPU
output. However, baselineCPU never reports the ARCH and other relevant fields,
that is being set in LibvirtConfigCPU by the LibvirtConfigCaps.
The absense of the arch field is causing the bug below.
Fixing it to simply update the LibvirtConfigCPU.

Change-Id: I9dd06fa44a232a333609fa115d05ad8822e21c0c
Closes-Bug: #1266534

commit_message:
Add boolean convertor to cells sync_instances API

cells sync_instances API contains "deleted" as the parameter, and the
parameter should be boolean. There are the other boolean parameters
such as "on_shared_storage" of evacuate API, they can be passed with
either boolean or string(e.g. "True").
For the consistency of whole Nova APIs, this patch adds boolean conv-
ertors to cells sync_instances API.

Change-Id: I4776539cfd723f302d10350757e1c341384c9ba2
Closes-Bug: #1261287

commit_message:
Moves negative tests from test_instance_actions

This change set moves the negative tests in
tempest/api/compute/servers/test_instance_actions
to a new file test_instance_actions_negative

Also removes usage of modules directly.

Note: HACKING.rst
The second requirement is that all negative tests must be added to a negative
test file. If such a file doesn't exist for the particular resource being
tested a new test file should be added

Change-Id: I6fd392e3fca84f7daeb3769ff59a8d5dadb900c3

commit_message:
Tests use cleanUp rather than tearDown

The tests were putting clean-up code in tearDown. Using tearDown
causes problems with developing and testing because if there's an
exception raised in setUp then tearDown is not called and this
typically affects other tests. For example, you'll get several
tests failing because one test's setUp failed and now the other
tests can't load fixtures.

Also, this should make it easier to switch to using fixtures since
fixtures use cleanUp.

Change-Id: I0d0d14ec34ebbeb9dbf0fe2fe3dd304b868bcf93

commit_message:
Remove skip_because in swift object expiry test

According to the comments in bug #1069849 container
listing will list an expired object (normal behavior).
This is up to the client to handle that a DELETE on
an expired object will return a 404 error.
delete_container method does not take care of any
HTTP return code for object deletion.

This patch remove the skip_because statement as the
test works as expected and not fails in tearDownClass.

This patch also add a test for metadata X-Delete-At.

Change-Id: I6c6efa151fd7b64684b25b049539680a3766e0cd

commit_message:
Python 3: Use HTTPMessage.get() rather than HTTPMessage.getheader()

In Python 2, get() is a synonym for getheader(), which does not exist in Python
3.

Closes-Bug: #1267987
Change-Id: I6989a6ea733e0a186e9e68a61aaa8c3e43a198a6

commit_message:
Change ListOpt default value from str or None to list

In keystone/common/config.py, some ListOpt config object was inited
with a string or None default value, it's incorrect. This patch modifies
their default value to list objects.

Change-Id: I2aec4f49d94e131d45f7dc9bfeb63b8d819d0bb1
Closes-Bug: #1259735

commit_message:
Revert "Whitelist external netaddr requirement"

This reverts commit 01dc81aa148adaa127281f197047636cf2d2c898.

The netaddr package is now hosted on PyPI, so this workaround is
not needed anymore.

Change-Id: I76957aa5e276036921696f27e18efb5494b33120
Closes-Bug: #1266513

commit_message:
Sync strutils from oslo

Sync strutils from oslo which fix safe_encode under py3, this gets
keystone CLI to properly output results.

84d461 Fix a bug in safe_encode where it returns a bytes object in py3

Closes-Bug: 1260824
Change-Id: Idf0f3a51f5cfe3077395b53da66a12955449861f

commit_message:
Documents keystone v3 API usage - part 1

docs/source/using-api.rst documents how to use the V2 API. This patch
starts the equivalent documentation (using-api-v3.rst) about how to
use Keystone v3 API. Introduction and Authentication sections have
been written.

Change-Id: I5a2d45d80ba712492717a75ac5901f5ca775daa4
Partial-Bug: #1260527

commit_message:
Fix get_column_num problem in heat-keystone-setup

get_column_num function searches the second line of command output,
to get the field number for a specific field.

But output of 'keystone user-list' may have an extra line: 'WARNING:
Bypassing authentication using a token & endpoint ...'

This messes up the functionality of get_column_num function

Closes-bug: #1260556
Change-Id: I8c6e7f939466154c5e31e6f019e20fb855e15878

Add a run_tempest.sh script

This commit adds a run_tempest.sh script which is used for running
tempest in the same manner that used to be handled by run_tests.sh.

Partially implements bp unit-tests

Change-Id: Id03d198b888ebd3673b2ca6fa895164910a42c4c

commit_message:
Make run_tests.sh for running unit tests

In other projects the run_tests.sh script is used for project
verification (ie running unit tests) However, because tempest didn't
have unit tests and is itself a test suite the run_tests.sh script was
used to execute the tempest tests. Now that we have unit tests starting
to trickle into tempest the run_tests.sh script can be used for it's
traditional purpose. So, this commit removes the tempest specific
functionality from run_tests.sh and makes it run the unit tests.

Partially implements bp unit-tests

Change-Id: Iac4e9d0908274a20c3d278b2c8d7e00949a1f36e

commit_message:
Controllable redirect handling

The requests library handles redirects as a browser would, which has the problem
that forwarding a POST will convert it to a GET. This is not necessarily
intuitive for an API. Handle all redirection manually and provide some
control over how far redirection can go.

Closes-Bug: 1267286
Change-Id: I24596a9c39cc29db28a66c3053ef3954b33abf90

commit_message:
Fixed a problem in iSCSI multipath

Multipathing during copy image to volume and copy volume to image
operations doesn't work properly if there are different targets
associated with different portals for a mulitpath device.

Change-Id: I65c93f3788020c944db0d3a55063a6415554ff11
Closes-Bug: #1266048

Hello Yassine, thanks for you working on this and #66005.

I'm interested in why you separated a complete change to two changes (this and #66005), I see each of them cover function and testing but IMO they are simple and whole change is small enough to get review as a single patch and I also see the same push pattern on your #65650 and #65653, #65914 (which not be organized by function and test even). So IMO can we push this type change as a single patch in future? of course I believe the separated patch is worth for get quick review if the change is big, but I consider this type changes is suitable for a single patch since it only change a single line to use six.StringIO instead of  StringIO.StringIO.

[{'created': '2013-12-09 15:28:10.000000000', 'message': 'races cause 404 when removing user from project

When removing a user from a project, the assignment manager retrieves a
list of all roles the user has on the project, then removes each role.
Each (user, role, project) tuple is removed with a separate call into
the driver. If, before a particular role has been removed, that role is
deleted by another request calling into the manager (i.e., via
delete_role), the call into the driver by the user removal request will
raise a RoleNotFound exception and the request will return an HTTP 404
error. Furthermore, any roles in the list after the exceptional role
will not be deleted.
This patch add try-except around the
driver.remove_role_from_user_and_project calls to catch the RoleNotFound
exceptions, so that roles after the exceptional role will be deleted as
expected, then 404 could be avoid.

Fixes bug #1257390

Change-Id: Ic48d869711d0275d402616c550fc0e7444b0a0d0

commit_message:
races cause 404 when removing user from project

When removing a user from a project, the assignment manager retrieves a
list of all roles the user has on the project, then removes each role.
Each (user, role, project) tuple is removed with a separate call into
the driver. If, before a particular role has been removed, that role is
deleted by another request calling into the manager (i.e., via
delete_role), the call into the driver by the user removal request will
raise a RoleNotFound exception and the request will return an HTTP 404
error. Furthermore, any roles in the list after the exceptional role
will not be deleted.
This patch add try-except around the
driver.remove_role_from_user_and_project calls to catch the RoleNotFound
exceptions, so that roles after the exceptional role will be deleted as
expected, and a 404 is not returned.

Closes-Bug: #1257390

Change-Id: Ic48d869711d0275d402616c550fc0e7444b0a0d0

commit_message:
Wrong marker sent to keystone

Removed nonsense marker that prevents charts grouped by project
working. Dropping also pagination for now, there is a UX design
in progress that would present how pagination should work.

Fixes bug 1260528

Change-Id: I3c2c2b2d0c3fcc6947f53a10441f9cd1440ef0fa

commit_message:
Add section for LVM driver

The config reference was missing a section for the default driver,
LVM. This adds a new section, with the config options needed to use
it and fixes the incorrect mention in the section lead-in.

Closes-Bug 1208205

Change-Id: Idefab5dbd69c37d637bc2a3f75880d8e341379ee

the controller and storage nodes.

'}]
commit_message:
Clarified database configuration steps for Block Storage

I clarified the database configuration steps for Block Storage for
consistency with the associated patch applied to Havana. I also added
a note for Ubuntu users to add the '[database]' section header if not
included with the default "cinder.conf" file. This patch covers both
the controller and storage nodes.

Change-Id: I6ae7072b2a98db00a6367213721f883072f8348b

commit_message:
Ensure that nova client prints dictionaries and arrays correctly

Print the dictionaries and arrays without the unicode tags.

The patch also updated tests that did not return valid data.

Change-Id: Ia787f98a9510b68beb3ceaf00c285ca5c934f5c0
Closes-bug: #1265002

commit_message:
VMware: update test file names

The tests files names all had prefix vmwareapi. This is no longer
needed as the test files are now under the vmwareapi directory.

The patch also fixed the permission for the file test_vm_util.py.

Change-Id: I87955a0a4d4d2b2c1dd55203658707ce7c6038f0

commit_message:
Align glance-api.conf rbd option defaults with config

DocImpact: The example glance-api.conf set different defaults than
what was hardcoded in the code. Change code defaults to those
in the config.

Preparation for generating glance-api.conf with oslo.config generator.

Change-Id: I424e6c5984dbdf5082852c40d97ab1e1a04926ea

commit_message:
Fix lxc rootfs attached two devices in some action

During resizing/rebooting a lxc container, create_domain action
will be called and lxc rootfs will be attached to device again.
So before this action, We need to teardown the container to
make sure lxc_root_device is detached when container is destroyed.

Closes-bug: #1243083
Related-bug: #1208387

Change-Id: Idd1862c7f212dc253b6273b07b020c86a94e658e

commit_message:
Ensure instance action event list in order

For two events also most happening at the same time, e.g. schedule and
run_instance, instance-action may fail to do the correct sorting because
the "create_at" column in db has the same value.

This change fixes this issue by sorting in "create_at" first, and then
in database generated "id" column, both in descending order.

Closes-bug: 1254764

Change-Id: I245a577ef2821fa7f3316bb8a21b7e6370498dd0

(6 inline comments)

Thank you for the patch, I think it makes sense to remove the asserts (particularly in the file where the imports are optional). I made a few comments/asked a couple of questions inline. Since in many files the warnings are already silenced, it seems to me we can get away with simply removing the asserts. Particularly in the forms init file, which raises a few concerns about maintenance."}, {'account_id': 8648, 'date': '2013-12-18 10:50:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thanks for the comments. I think that __all__ should do more than just replace those asserts -- it also makes sure that a situation like that in forms.py never happens again.

The __all__ in forms.py doesn't need to be maintained -- all those imported modules are there only for backwards compatibility, and I hope that we can gradually remove them at some point, by making sure they are imported from django, as they should, and not from horizon. I am at least sure that we never want to add to them.

I will remove the __all__ from the __init__.py files, you are right that they don't make much sense in there."}, {'account_id': 8648, 'date': '2013-12-18 10:56:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: (1 inline comment)

'}, {'account_id': 4978, 'date': '2013-12-18 10:57:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Right, for some reason I thought the forms's __all__ list was listing the horizon forms submodules, but you're right. We don't want to add to this! I'm somewhat confident/hopeful any attempt to "import *" like this in the future would be tut-tuted severely in reviews though.'}, {'account_id': 8648, 'date': '2013-12-18 11:01:43.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-12-18 11:49:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Works for me

commit_message:
Remove redundant meter (name,type,unit) tuples from Resource model

Fixes bug 1267162

Previously, a list of meter (name,type,unit) tuples with per-sample
cardinality was added to the Resource model by the storage driver
get_resource method.

However this potentially huge and highly repetitive list was then
promptly discarded by the API layer, as the meter links in the API
Resource representation are populated via subsequent calls into
the storage driver get_meters method.

Now, we avoid the scaling issue by suppressing the creation of
this unused meter list.

Change-Id: I18dee7552836c724798ea1340e2e933c09d8a294
(cherry picked from commit 7c4c0e8fc098fbadec2e30ea2bdf1068b5b4288a)

commit_message:
3PAR: Raise Ex when del snapshot with depend vol

Deleting a 3PAR snapshot can result in an HTTP Conflict error message,
such as when a volume is dependent on it.
Previously, this exception was not caught, and the state was set
to "Error_Deleting" with no recovery path.
The code was updated to catch this exception and raise a
SnapShotIsBusy exception with an appropriate error message.
The state reverts back to 'Available' allowing the user to try again
after removing the dependency.

Change-Id: Ibe8c5d581af10c85397c37993c49f8fc3bce8620
Closes-Bug: #1250249

commit_message:
Add missing oslo/__init__.py

Add the missing oslo/__init__.py, since its absence seems to prevent
devstack's setup.py-develop-from-git install of oslo.rootwrap from
operating correctly.

Change-Id: I861ae7024554a8ba9b046c1048eccf1bcea69100

commit_message:
Support list deleted servers for admin

Nova api supported a parameter named 'deleted' which allow Admin to list
deleted servers. This patch make novaclient support this.

Add scheduler_hints field to Instance table

Add a column in the Instance table to store scheduler_hints field.

Co-Author: Yassine Lamgarchal <yassine.lamgarchal@enovance.com>

Change-Id: I0e102f5973e02bbfda1999fb0bca0b94e349ed56
Implements part of bp validate-targethost-live-migration

commit_message:
Remove duplicate blockdev filter line

The last one of a duplicate line wins, and that one was
too restrictive. Merge it into one entry that covers both cases.

Change-Id: I36b8ba6d2b6c70abda09e07f59100057e09f7e97
Closes-Bug: #1267847

commit_message:
Handle UnicodeEncodeError in validate_integer

validate_integer can be potentially passed user
supplied data which causes a UnicodeEncodeError
exception during validation rather than just ValueError.
This change handles the UnicodeEncode exception
so validate_integer treats it as invalid input.

Change-Id: I5177789299b02448ed53e1b7fc23ccdaee1b70d3

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-12-27 14:49:45.000000000', 'message': "Fix image cache periodic task concurrent access bug

There is no lock between image cache periodic task and nova
delete operation, so there can exist rare case that after
examination of the disk file in image cache thread, the
disk file was removed right after that and it will raise
an exception about it.

This fix catch the exception and ignore it. It will defer
the image cache clean to next round image cache periodic task
it's not harmful. Refer to the comments in bug
https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/1261442 for detail info

Change-Id: I3a431bf389658f976edf5c847c04b7e0aac496fd
Closes-Bug: #1261442
"}, {'created': '2013-12-30 03:28:01.000000000', 'message': "Fix image cache periodic task concurrent access bug

This fix catch the exception and ignore a disk file absent
exception. It will defer the image cache clean to next round
image cache periodic task because it's not harmful.
https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/1261442 has detailed

commit_message:
Fix image cache periodic task concurrent access bug

This fix catch the exception and ignore a disk file absent
exception. It will defer the image cache clean to next round
image cache periodic task because it's not harmful.
Refer to detailed info, log analysis and root cause in defect.

Change-Id: I3a431bf389658f976edf5c847c04b7e0aac496fd
Closes-Bug: #1261442

commit_message:
Adds new method nova.utils.get_hash_str

Some modules are using their own method to generate hex from
string.
This patch adds a new method "get_hash_str" in nova.utils and
cleans every module needs to use it.

Change-Id: I2fa7dd2ea12c1d516224132d13454d109bb6c1e3

I'm afraid I don't understand this well enough to score this review.  I'm not sure lifeless's comments have been addressed, especially since I still a dependency on haproxy in keepalived.conf."}, {'account_id': 7582, 'date': '2013-12-15 19:29:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

To be sure, by dependency between keepalived and haproxy you mean usage of virtual_ip parameter?

Both elements are really independent - keepalived is used for failover on nodes level (just decides which node in "keepalived cluster" receives packets comming to the virtual IP), haproxy does failover on service level.

You can use e.g. pacemaker+haproxy instead of keepalived+haproxy, also you can use keepalived with other service than haproxy (e.g. db cluster).

So both elements can live without each other but both need to know virtual_ip.'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-12-15 23:07:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

On Fedora 20, the mysqld service is called mariadb.  While there is a
symlink from mysqld->mariadb, there is an issue with that approach and
systemd. So, we need to explicitally enable mariadb if the mysqld
enablement fails.

Change-Id: Ideee870aba5275987233c8411d57024ac7def695
See: https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1014311
'}]
commit_message:
Enable mariadb service.

On Fedora 20, the mysqld service is called mariadb.  While there is a
symlink from mysqld->mariadb, there is an issue with that approach and
systemd. So, we need to explicitally enable mariadb if the mysqld
enablement fails.

Change-Id: Ideee870aba5275987233c8411d57024ac7def695
See: https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1014311

commit_message:
bash8: fix bash8 warning

This patch removes the following bash8 warnings.

> /devstack/ $ ./run_tests.sh
> Running bash8...
> E003: Indent not multiple of 4: '             wget -c $image_url -O $FILES/$IMAGE_FNAME'
>  - functions: L1367
> E003: Indent not multiple of 4: '             if [[ $? -ne 0 ]]; then'
>  - functions: L1368
> E003: Indent not multiple of 4: '                 echo "Not found: $image_url"'
>  - functions: L1369
> E003: Indent not multiple of 4: '                 return'
>  - functions: L1370
> E003: Indent not multiple of 4: '             fi'
>  - functions: L1371
> E003: Indent not multiple of 4: '                                 `"should use a descriptor-data pair."'
>  - functions: L1423
> E003: Indent not multiple of 4: '                         `" Attempt to retrieve the *-flat.vmdk: $flat_url"'
>  - functions: L1438
> E003: Indent not multiple of 4: '                             `" Attempt to retrieve the descriptor *.vmdk: $descriptor_url"'
>  - functions: L1477
> E003: Indent not multiple of 4: '                         warn $LINENO "Descriptor not found $descriptor_url"'
>  - functions: L1492
> E003: Indent not multiple of 4: '                         descriptor_found=false'
>  - functions: L1493
> E003: Indent not multiple of 4: '                 fi'
>  - functions: L1501
> E003: Indent not multiple of 4: '             fi'
>  - functions: L1502
> E003: Indent not multiple of 4: '             #TODO(alegendre): handle streamOptimized once supported by the VMware driver.'
>  - functions: L1503
> E003: Indent not multiple of 4: '             vmdk_disktype="preallocated"'
>  - functions: L1504
> 14 bash8 error(s) found

Change-Id: Icf2cddf283192a50253ccfa697c2d32eec75b4ba
Closes-Bug: #1267716

commit_message:
Fix test_notifier_logger for Python 3

 * Get the current line at runtime, don't hardcode the line number
 * Only strip last character of the filename if it ends with ".pyc"
   or ".pyo".  On Python 3, import automatically replaces .pyc and
   .pyo with .py.
 * Use threading.current_thread().ident to get the identifier of the
   current thread. The get_ident() function is available in thread
   module in Python 2, but in threading module in Python 3. And on
   Python 3, logging.thread symbol does not exist anymore.

Change-Id: I3f248bb860caafaf38eefcf440d36b9bebc8f05e

A checkout listener can be added to sqlalchemy to be able to
handle database disconnect pessimistically and avoid an error in
the event of a DB restart or simply a temp connection issue due
to network glitches. At the moment only mysql is enabled with

Oslo version in change I5563360b43c4b648f5b035099b0e1d2e71d32503

commit_message:
Oslo sync to recover from db2 server disconnects

A checkout listener can be added to sqlalchemy to be able to
handle database disconnect pessimistically and avoid an error in
the event of a DB restart or simply a temp connection issue due
to network glitches. At the moment only mysql is enabled with
this feature. This patch enables db2 as well.

Oslo version in change I5563360b43c4b648f5b035099b0e1d2e71d32503

Partial-Bug: #1231657
Change-Id: I218ef9836f2e0f135897007d2e53354eb1248422

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-12-19 13:58:54.000000000', 'message': 'Fix try/except syntax for Python 3

"except (IOError, errors):" fails with a TypeError if errors is a tuple on
Python 3, whereas it was accepted in Python 2.

Change-Id: I65cfb60af87e76fdf2d37043fb106adbd4586fb9
'}]
commit_message:
Fix try/except syntax for Python 3

"except (IOError, errors):" fails with a TypeError if errors is a tuple on
Python 3, whereas it was accepted in Python 2.

Change-Id: I65cfb60af87e76fdf2d37043fb106adbd4586fb9

commit_message:
Add test to port_security to test with security_groups

This patch adds a missing testcase to the port_security tests to test
for creating a port with port_security_enabled=False and passing in
a security group.

Closes-bug: #1267246
Change-Id: Ifb5a5571f016a5d7c5b5075c97dc27279cd79bb7

The previous comments show that the QA group needs to better define "negative test".  It appears that in these test cases, "negative" has meant any test which tests for the absence of some feature or component.  This is a valid interpretation.  Now a commenter has proposed that "negative" tests should test for cases where exceptions are expected to be thrown.  This is also a valid interpretation.

Clarification of the definition of "negative tests" in a QA wiki page will improve effectiveness and efficiency of the test developers.  I'll either start a bug or blueprint to track this.

I believe in this instance, until we have clarification, these tests should either remain here, or be moved back to the "positive test" section as we do not want to lose coverage.'}, {'account_id': 8641, 'date': '2013-11-10 00:06:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: (1 inline comment)

add a negative test for test_images

over to it, and add a negative test in it.

commit_message:
Add HexInteger field type in object models

In PCI devices or PCI stats in compute nodes, the numbers of domain, bus, slot
and function are interpreted as hexadecimal numbers, for instance.

So, add a new type based on integer to stand for those hexadecimal numbers.

Implements: blueprint icehouse-objects
Related to blueprint icehouse-objects.

Change-Id: I820ca7f481e897c97fe3f11c1bf35efa71fa0ab7

commit_message:
Lower NotFound exception log level

Module api.v2.resource will log NotFound as an exception, which is not
suitable, this patch lowers it to info level.

NOTE: openstack.common.rpc.amqp also log NotFound exception as an error,
but this patch only aims at api module.

Partial-Bug: #1048320
Change-Id: I5ef9f3eb9ba2d9dddb9db17df2949cde0ae153db

commit_message:
Add equality check into NovaObject and ObjectList

Add __eq__ and __ne__ into objects and object lists, so objects and object
lists can compare objects'(object lists') and dictionaries'(lists') equality.

Related to blueprint icehouse-objects.

Change-Id: I431ed3db84ab87968bdf520915c7601093d5685e

commit_message:
WIP: Defined a resource to query available language packs.

We want the ability to specify the language pack that should be used
to build a DU. For this, we need the ability to query the language
packs that are currently available. Defined a resource to query
available language packs. The resource is defined at
(/v1/language_packs).

Partly implements: blueprint specify-lang-pack

This work assumes controller, dispatcher, handler separation that
Murali has proposed.

Continuing to work on defining nova objects for language packs
needed as part of this.

Change-Id: Ib5a05908baffb235f0ae59fb2e2a9a973b76bd46

commit_message:
Modified source text for message re: cinder volume directory

Augmented the text that describes the cinder volume dir to
mention how the dir is automatically created by the VMDK
driver, if it doesn't already exist.

Change-Id: I9cd469c6748636790fd5ec8a05036e4fb4ea68a1
Closes-Bug: #1265044

commit_message:
Enable multi-threaded nova-conductor

Just like I09f4c6f57e71982b8c7fc92645b3ebec12ff1348, enable
multi-threaded nova-conductor.  This feature was merged into nova in
I8698997d211d7617ee14a1c6113056a694d70620.

Change-Id: Id7042284e81bd64092a400d24a3170ce07beb08c

commit_message:
The private method _text_node should be used as function

If the class method does not reference any of the class attributes
it may be more clear to define the method as a static function instead.

Change-Id: I273e00fc4ab6fecafcd7bdeaf3b809a6688025c5

commit_message:
Log when quarantining an object

When you're trying to troubleshoot why all your objects are getting
quarantined, it's really nice to have some logging. If nothing else,
it's nice to know which process did it.

Change-Id: I6e8be6df938659f7392891df9336ed70bd155706

commit_message:
Allow some instance polling periodic tasks to hit db slave

If your deployment has a slave configured, poll_*instance* periodic
tasks will send their reads to the slave. If you have no slave
configured, there is no change to behavior.

Note for developers, I have targeted all the easy tasks. By this I
mean tasks that were already using the InstanceList object and the
get_all_by_filters or get_all_by_host methods. I will slaveify the
other tasks in seperate reviews since they also require conversion
to using objects.

Change-Id: I4bead5d350d633d726d4564b4bc1baec2e2977b7
Partially-implements: blueprint periodic-tasks-to-db-slave

commit_message:
Python 3: use six.iteritems() instead of iteritems()

six.iteritems() replaces dictionary.iteritems() on Python 2 and
dictionary.items() on Python 3.

Change-Id: Ie5efa65c0a992e8136087a7b78ab8e8ce967326e

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-10-14 11:28:57.000000000', 'message': 'xenapi: resize up ephemeral disks

After adding the ability to migrate ephemeral disks, we were unable to
perform any resize of ephemeral disks.

This change implements the ability to increase the size of ephemeral
disks, if that is required be the selected flavor.

As with the root disk, we attempt to expand the partition and filesystem
where possible, but only if auto_disk_config=True.

However, after this change, you will still not be able to resize down
the ephemeral disks. This function has proved very error prone when
dealing with root disks, so we are not implementing this feature for
ephemeral disks, and will error on requests to reduce the size of
ephemeral disks.

Implements blueprint xenapi-resize-ephemeral-disks
Change-Id: I218e9db9f5c912335c96da9831b300513213d33d

commit_message:
xenapi: resize up ephemeral disks

After adding the ability to migrate ephemeral disks, we were unable to
perform any resize of ephemeral disks.

This change implements the ability to increase the size of ephemeral
disks, if that is required be the selected flavor.

Unlike with the root disk, we attempt to expand the partition and
filesystem will never be touched by the resize up process.

However, after this change, you will still not be able to resize down
the ephemeral disks. This function has proved very error prone when
dealing with root disks, so we are not implementing this feature for
ephemeral disks, and will error on requests to reduce the size of
ephemeral disks.

Implements blueprint xenapi-resize-ephemeral-disks
Change-Id: I218e9db9f5c912335c96da9831b300513213d33d

commit_message:
xenapi: refactor generate_ephemeral

Refactoring generate_ephemeral so it will be easier to generate
individual ephemeral disks when required.

Needed by blueprint xenapi-resize-ephemeral-disks
Change-Id: I7032bd4c7d80adb62f8d5ece085170c6b89e267d

commit_message:
xenapi: refactor resize_up_root_vdi

Some refactoring to move things into vm_utils where possible, and
setting the stage for resizing ephemeral disks.

Needed by blueprint xenapi-resize-ephemeral-disks
Change-Id: Iba26ddb8b3d9041981317c47bb3b53733c004cea

Add base class for Telemetry tests

This patch adds the base class for all Telemetry tests.

Partially implements: blueprint add-basic-ceilometer-tests

Change-Id: If467d05bceb4f5c29a7cac6c83be6fc8aae159c8

commit_message:
Change "peer_cidrs" field to MultiIpField

Change "peer_cidrs" field from IPField to MultiIpField.
This will help to choose a list of subnets for IPSec Site Connection
instead of one subnet only.
Some tests are also added.

Fixes bug 1257253

Change-Id: Ib68bd0ad7373694fba4a04f9486bb31410eb322f

commit_message:
Logging excepthook: print exception info if debug=True

Exception info is only printed by this function if verbose=True.
Since debug is considered a log level with more information than
verbose (INFO), exception info should also be printed when only
debug=True.

Change-Id: I349dc76320911600accc2acdb02d9d94710cfc85

I THINK the code-change looks good.  I'm trying to work through the different cases:

time-diff is positive and greater than threshold:  Log them out.
time-diff is positive and less than threshold: Leave them logged in.
time-diff is negative and less than threshold: The internal timing of things is not amazingly synced up, but any time difference is small enough to leave them logged in?
time-diff is negative and greater than threshold:  Something is quite a bit out of sync, log them out for safety?  (Do I have this correct?)

I just don't understand the full implications of the negative time-diffs."}, {'account_id': 2455, 'date': '2013-12-20 13:14:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

commit_message:
Fixing time difference calculation in middleware

taking the diff of two times and accessing seconds does not work
robustly especially across load balanced nodes

Change-Id: If218d100d25c544b37a2517bd260838092a5f8cf
Closes-bug: #1243277

commit_message:
Remove dupl. for get_resources in adv. services

There is duplication of logic related to creating API resources
for advanced services extensions. Extracted the common logic
out into a new module that can be used by the services.
There are already UT cases in the services that exercises
the logic, so no new tests were added.

Change-Id: Ib52e2de6f215a1755f11a382dc4451a05ce3b147
Closes-Bug: 1258656

commit_message:
VXLAN support

This patch is implementing support for VXLAN tunnel
type for OVS plugin.

Refactored neutron::plugins::ml2::validate_* to functions
so they can be used in other manifests in module.

Change-Id: Ic51ed794b27069809a151dc365ca108c8300c277

commit_message:
Added session_persistence property to VIP

Added new property session_persistance to the OS::Neutron::LoadBalancer
resource attribute VIP. Now user can configure session stickness feature
in Neutron LBaaS.

Change-Id: I9afd1a8c222110899a90a940e7a549278c4467b7
Closes-Bug: #1259078

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-01-10 21:02:22.000000000', 'message': 'DO NOT MERGE: Add support for parallel testr workers in Keystone

---
TEST PATCHSET TO GET MORE DEBUGGING OUT OF JENKINS RUNTIME VIA DOGPILE DEBUG
---

Add support for parallel testr workers in Keystone. This change
forces an override of the SQLite DB path for tests to use a
per-worker (based on PID) temp directory. The keystoneclient,
keystoneclient_sql, and certficate setup tests are grouped onto
a single worker to limit edge cases and limit the amount of
external (keystoneclient library) downloading.

Support to "unset" an override using self.reset_opt_in_group has
been added to allow for checking the configuration option behaviors
that touch the database.connection option (e.g. test_config and
ensuring the deprecated sql 'connection' options continue to
work).

For non-SQLite databases to be used, in .testr.conf the
'test_run_concurrency' line must be uncommented, as the support
to handle on-demand postgres, mysql, etc databases to be created
will come in a subsequent change.  Currently non-sqlite databases
cannot be used in tests with parallel testr workers.

Each worker uses a subdirectory of keystone/tests/tmp based upon
the PID. When the worker exists (via the use of atexit), the
worker-specific PID directory is automatically removed.

Change-Id: I1ca2983c47fb88eda670d49234d66b42a2ef1f62

commit_message:
DO NOT MERGE: Add support for parallel testr workers in Keystone

---
TEST PATCHSET TO GET MORE DEBUGGING OUT OF JENKINS RUNTIME VIA DOGPILE DEBUG
---

Add support for parallel testr workers in Keystone. This change
forces an override of the SQLite DB path for tests to use a
per-worker (based on PID) temp directory. The keystoneclient,
keystoneclient_sql, and certficate setup tests are grouped onto
a single worker to limit edge cases and limit the amount of
external (keystoneclient library) downloading.

Support to "unset" an override using self.reset_opt_in_group has
been added to allow for checking the configuration option behaviors
that touch the database.connection option (e.g. test_config and
ensuring the deprecated sql 'connection' options continue to
work).

For non-SQLite databases to be used, in .testr.conf the
'test_run_concurrency' line must be uncommented, as the support
to handle on-demand postgres, mysql, etc databases to be created
will come in a subsequent change.  Currently non-sqlite databases
cannot be used in tests with parallel testr workers.

Each worker uses a subdirectory of keystone/tests/tmp based upon
the PID. When the worker exists (via the use of atexit), the
worker-specific PID directory is automatically removed.

commit_message:
Add use case to USECASES.md

	It is a use case listed in https://wiki.openstack.org/
	wiki/Puppet-openstack/ceph-blueprint

	Adding the ceph blueprint in USECASES.md

	Adding a link in the README.md

Closes-Bug: #1243333

Change-Id: Iff1415cace170676c9ff8ec57d05d9bd6bf8ccdf
Blueprint: Add the "I want to spawn a cluster configured with continuous integration" use case to USECASES.md
Signed-off-by: Romain Salot <romain.salot@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Adding IDH plugin basic implementation

Functionality:

* install and provision Intel Hadoop Manager and Intel Hadoop
* configure Intel Hadoop to use Cinder volumes as HDFS backend
* manual cluster scaling support
* Swift integration
* cluster configs - the same configs as in Vanilla Hadoop
* configs validation - the same as in Vanilla plugin

This is initial version. It doesn't cover bugs filed here:
https://bugs.launchpad.net/savanna/+bugs?field.searchtext=%7BIDH%5D

Co-Authored-By: Andrew Lazarev <alazarev@mirantis.com>

Implements blueprint idh-savanna-plugin

Change-Id: I70363869b61d73222d247b566d499c2fd6fb9201

[{'created': '2014-01-10 19:06:02.000000000', 'message': 'Fixed database configuration steps for Block Storage

I changed the database configuration steps for Block Storage from the
legacy 'sql_connection' key under the '[DEFAULT]' section to the new
'connection' key under the '[database]' section common to other
services. I also added a note for Ubuntu users to add the '[database]'
section header if not included with the default "cinder.conf" file.
This patch covers both the controller and storage nodes.

Change-Id: I12fdb940c0831c052bc5a4a0328112a72e505d34
Closes-Bug: #1245880

commit_message:
Fixed database configuration steps for Block Storage

I changed the database configuration steps for Block Storage from the
legacy 'sql_connection' key under the '[DEFAULT]' section to the new
'connection' key under the '[database]' section common to other
services. I also added a note for Ubuntu users to add the '[database]'
section header if not included with the default "cinder.conf" file.
This patch covers both the controller and storage nodes.

Change-Id: I12fdb940c0831c052bc5a4a0328112a72e505d34
Closes-Bug: #1245880

log warning, when $SERVICE_HOST is localhost

Warn users, if heat-keystone-setup can only use localhost as $SERVICE_HOST.
And remove an extra whitespace.

commit_message:
Raise max header size to accommodate large tokens.

The max header is exceeded in the following scenario
- Auth tokens built with a keystone v3 API catalog
- A catalog with approximately 8 or more endpoints defined

An equivalent fix will be required for all projects which use
eventlet.wsgi.

Copied from https://review.openstack.org/#/c/33362/

Closes-Bug: 1190149

Change-Id: I3fcb196b25a7a477b799c8dfa2ff5115977ca06d

commit_message:
Move autobinding to task base class

The autobinding functionality is more of a
general task function so it is nice to have it
available for use in the root base class instead
of being an auxilary method.

Change-Id: I75abed25cb0bf165f61f8317e3cb1a62a3f9bf4a

commit_message:
Use correct auth context inside pxe driver

Until now, general auth context was used inside the pxe driver
making it fail when authenticating against glance. We should be using
instead task.context

Change-Id: I173b912c67ab77dda433d2f1f93e674852b7d054
Closes-Bug: #1266201

commit_message:
Changed nova-network install condition

openstack-network::server does not modify a node if
node['openstack']['compute']['network']['service_type'] is 'nova'.

Change check to use service_type attribute instead of server recipe so
that nova-network can be installed when using allinone-compute.

Change-Id: Iab969b30767d1d47fd5b55e805593a8d8548f0e9
Closes-Bug: #1267411

Instead of using the collections isinstance
check use the one provided in the six
module that takes into account other ways to
detect callability.

commit_message:
Assert functor task revert/execute are callable

Use the six module to assert that the provided
execute and revert functors are callable to avoid
late failures that would occur later when trying
to execute.

Change-Id: I599f2ad4071babcd3a3e363261f3c8cd0dee49b8

commit_message:
Refactor task handler binding

Instead of using a dictionary of handler mappings
use a dict[event] -> list of handler mappings, this
allows the same function/handler to be bound more than
once (which can be useful to do, depending on handler
specifications) and to allow for removal of these handlers
find the first match and remove it using the reflection
callback comparison routine.

Change-Id: Ied31dd893502ec91a48f7d2e1ef2cd4553a07f89

    return e"}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2013-12-16 11:11:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: (1 inline comment)

'}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2013-12-16 11:16:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Thanks for the review. Please see my comment in patch set 1. I am sure why each WSGI middleware should deal with webob exception specially (webob is just a framework to make it easy to implement WSGI app).'}, {'account_id': 8907, 'date': '2013-12-16 11:24:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

'}, {'account_id': 6928, 'date': '2014-01-03 23:54:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(2 inline comments)

A couple of minor things inline that I'd like to see cleaned up.

Regarding the exception handling, I'm a little confused by the previous discussion.  I think I understand why we don't want to directly return webob exceptions, but isn't that the purpose of the wsgify decorator?  If not, aren't we making everything a webob exception anyway in this middleware?

I'm not necessarily opposed to the way it works now, but I'm wondering if forcing everything to be the same type of error is going to limit the usefulness of this.  It's also possible I'm completely misunderstanding how it works.  I'm definitely not a middleware expert. :-)"}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2014-01-10 10:27:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: (2 inline comments)

Thanks for the review.

Regarding the exception handling, I am not sure whether throwing webob exception outside of a WSGI application/middleware is allowed or not. Some WSGI application is implemented by using webob but some do not. In my understanding webob exception and wsgi decorator make it easy to implement an WSGI application but it should be caught inside an application. Assume this middleware converts webob exception to a corresponding WSGI response. It works as expected as long as this middleware directly catches the exception, but if we insert another middleware between two application in a pipeline, the new middleware will catch the exception and the behavior changes.
I think raising webob exception outside an application does not follow WSGI spec and it is some kind of bug.

Another point is whether this middleware should be aware of webob exeception from other application specially.
I choose webob as an implementation choice of this middleware, but it is just a choice.
If we use other implemetation way we wouldn't know webob exception. I think an implementaiton of an application
should be independent from implemetations of other applications in WSGI concept.

I am not a middleware expert too, so I would like to know opinions from other reviews.

Does it make sense?"}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2014-01-10 10:28:59.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-01-10 10:50:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Works for me

'}, {'account_id': 8907, 'date': '2014-01-10 10:51:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

I completely agree with Akihiro points.

Also it won't limit http codes to be only 500, cause any specific HttpException is catched by wsgify decorator and passed as valid response."}, {'account_id': 6928, 'date': '2014-01-10 16:15:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

Okay, I read up on wsgify some more and it looks like this will work.  The decorator catches any webob.exc exceptions and converts them to wsgi responses, so this exception handler should never catch any of those because the middleware it's wrapping would have handled them already.  That's what I was misunderstanding before.

Added Julien because I think he has more experience with middleware than I do."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-01-10 18:02:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: No score

commit_message:
Filling out initial rubocop support for metadata.rb and the Gemfile.

https://blueprints.launchpad.net/openstack-chef/+spec/lint-and-unit-testing-for-havana
Removing tailor, cleaning up metadata and Gemfile and adding TESTING.md. Will
remove the .rubocop-todo.yml once the rest of the Rubocop support is filled out

* updating chefspec to 3.1.4 (for chefspec coverage)

Addresses: blueprint rubocop-for-network
Change-Id: I9c9c5b48f3e1174b1e7ec7b5451a6ad9fd82b5e0

commit_message:
Revert "Amended config instructions for cinder.config"

This reverts commit adfc7259f42f80588e138a3c210be0b53a89af8b
(not reverted: change of wording choosing -> choice)

The original text is correct for Icehouse. For Havana, connection in section DEFAULT is a deprecated setup.

Fix for cinder.conf file for Icehouse:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/61736/

Change-Id: I001797be9b9421d6818ed902d494bd133bf41b79

commit_message:
ensure sysctl.d exists (it does not by default on CentOS)

add a block to create /etc/sysctl.d, which is created by default
on ubuntu, but not centOS (though as of centOS 6.2, it is supported)

Change-Id: Id8011d7ef91cc13182f45adc201a3c66c8e891cd
Closes-Bug: #1266914
Implements: blueprint centos-rhel-for-common

commit_message:
updating version specification

Updating the way versioning is done to line up with other projects
in openstack. This change makes it so a commit will no longer be
required update the version of this package, now tagging will
handle updating the version.

Change-Id: I4b5a1674cbeedba5b2afe3aef64dd10156022ff7

This patch adds the image_location_quota config option. This allows

commit_message:
Add config option to limit image locations

This patch adds the image_location_quota config option. This allows
a deployer to limit the number of image locations allowed on an image.
The default value is 10. Users will only be able to update an image
if the result of the transaction would be under this limit. This
behavior is intended to be similar to 'quota_metadata_items' in Nova.

We have implemented the same limit for image properties, members and tags,
see:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/56981/
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/59563/
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/58056/

docImpact
Closes-Bug: #1259031

Change-Id: I0e0033a1d11be267144e8e10b730bb6331263d4c

The following migration 50e86cb2637a called
op.rename_table('neutron_nvp_port_mapping', 'neutron_nsx_port_mappings')
though the table name was actually quantum_nvp_port_mapping. Because of this
the quantum_id->nvp_id mapping was never migrated over to the new table and
you would be left with a quantum_nvp_port_mapping table hanging around.

instead of quantum_nvp_port_mapping. This patch addresses this issues. Below
show the commands and output used to test this as I figured it would be helpful
to see.

commit_message:
Fix Migration 50e86cb2637a and 38335592a0dc

When the rename of quantum->neutron occurred here ee3fe4e8 it also renamed
the the table creation from quantum_nvp_port_mapping to
neutron_nvp_port_mapping. This went undetected for a long time because
when neutron-server starts up it pushes down the scheme for tables that
are not there so the table would be created.

Because of this the following migration 50e86cb2637a called
op.rename_table('neutron_nvp_port_mapping', 'neutron_nsx_port_mappings')
though the table name being used was quantum_nvp_port_mapping. Because of this
the quantum_id->nvp_id mapping was never migrated over to the new table and
you would be left with a quantum_nvp_port_mapping table hanging around.

In addition, the downgrade would rename the table to neutron_nvp_port_mapping
instead of quantum_nvp_port_mapping. This patch addresses this issues.

Change-Id: I4f80b7b9dc56996ecd83826ee65918f5311c7c4f
Closes-bug: #1267619

commit_message:
Fix auth_token middleware test invalid cross-device link issue

Fixes path of temporary files, containing token revocation lists,
which weren't in the appropriate directory. File renaming now works
properly since source and destination files are in the same directory,
and therefore on the same partition.

Added to .gitignore temporary files generated during tests, that are
not being removed at the end of test.

Change-Id: I21ff81419313f4205ebe552556e27b86135fd096
Closes-Bug: #1265190

commit_message:
Delete a BuildError server

If a server creation fails with create_test_server() in setUpClass,
the server would not be removed because tearDownclass is not called.
As the result, many BuildError servers are created and "Quota exceeded"
happens if server creations continue to fail.

This patch makes create_test_server() removes a server when BuildError
happens for avoiding "Quota exceeded" exception and investigating the
original problem which is due to the BuildError.

Change-Id: I55bb386bbea550de11cc7a81c5d056680057523b
Related-Bug: #1257641

commit_message:
Install tcpdump on Fedora

Tcpdump has a fairly small footprint and should be installed to all
images (it currently is on the ubuntu image by default). Sometimes the
reason you need it is also the reason its to late to get it.

Change-Id: I4849157515b389d534bdee755cdac6b0768fcb29

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-01-09 20:41:09.000000000', 'message': "Implement dhcp-all-interfaces for systemd.

Includes:

 * Enhancements to the generate-interfaces-file.sh script
 so that it generates ifcfg network-scripts for
 distros like Fedora/RHEL.

 * Includes a new dhcp-all-interfaces.service systemd
 script which ensures network interfaces get generated
 before the network service starts on Fedora.

 * Add a new disable_interface function to
 generate-interfaces-file.sh which (on Fedora)
 will delete the ifcfg config for an interface which
 isn't plugged in.
 This is important because ifcfg-eth0 exists by default
 and we want to remove it if the NIC isn't connected.
 Previous behaviour on Ubuntu is unchanged and the
 generate-interfaces-file.sh just logs it as skipped.

 * General doc updates...

I tested this on a multi-nic machine w/ Fedora where the first NIC
exists but was not connected.

Change-Id: Ia99e312539da43caefd72aa60398d43dac5dcc8f
Closes-Bug: 1239880

 script which ensures network interfaces get generated
 before the network service starts on Fedora.

 * Add a new disable_interface function to
 generate-interfaces-file.sh which (on Fedora)
 will delete the ifcfg config for an interface which
 isn't plugged in.
 This is important because ifcfg-eth0 exists by default
 and we want to remove it if the NIC isn't connected.
 Previous behaviour on Ubuntu is unchanged and the
 generate-interfaces-file.sh just logs it as skipped.

 * General doc updates...

I tested this on a multi-nic machine w/ Fedora where the first NIC
exists but was not connected.

Change-Id: Ia99e312539da43caefd72aa60398d43dac5dcc8f
Closes-Bug: 1239880

commit_message:
Implement dhcp-all-interfaces for systemd.

Includes:

 * Enhancements to the generate-interfaces-file.sh script
 so that it generates ifcfg network-scripts for
 distros like Fedora/RHEL.

 * Includes a new dhcp-all-interfaces.service systemd
 script which ensures network interfaces get generated
 before the network service starts on Fedora.

 * Add a new disable_interface function to
 generate-interfaces-file.sh which (on Fedora)
 will delete the ifcfg config for an interface which
 isn't plugged in.
 This is important because ifcfg-eth0 exists by default
 and we want to remove it if the NIC isn't connected.
 Previous behaviour on Ubuntu is unchanged and the
 generate-interfaces-file.sh just logs it as skipped.

 * General doc updates...

I tested this on a multi-nic machine w/ Fedora where the first NIC
exists but was not connected.

Change-Id: Ia99e312539da43caefd72aa60398d43dac5dcc8f
Closes-Bug: 1239880

commit_message:
Displaying curl commands for nova and cinder calls

When using the -v option, displays curl equivalent commands and http
messages exchanged with the nova and cinder API servers. Displays the
same messages as those displayed with the --debug option of
python-novaclient and python-cinderclient.

Implements: blueprint curl-commands-in-debugging-messages for nova and
cinder related calls

Change-Id: Ibc8ef79d874334585b81d652b9c7df9e874fffa9

commit_message:
Utilizes assertIsNone and assertIsNotNone

Using assertEqual/assertNotEqual to test if an element
is or is not None is too python2.4.
Our unit testing framework supports assertIsNone and assertIsNotNone
which were created for these types of tests.

Change-Id: I29f915ae79bf4f8e9298c5de5d6087828fb0ca4f

commit_message:
Python 3: use six.iteritems() instead of iteritems()

six.iteritems() replaces dictionary.iteritems() on Python 2 and
dictionary.items() on Python 3.

Change-Id: I3c9d7dff76e372de0ca9f9b88d1c76b7fc1760c4

commit_message:
Implements: docker instance name matches UUID

passes the instance uuid to docker API for naming
of running container to make it easier to
correllate instance to container.

* added unit tests, trouble running them locally, so hope
they work *hugs jenkins*

Change-Id: Ic4d6338e1e9eab936ecb32edd1c5c63e09d77814

commit_message:
Remove noop code

All these lines of code did was get a logger. Getting a logger is
a noop.

The comment says that this code was supposed to change the logging
configuration but it doesn't do that. Also, this isn't the correct
way to change the logging configuration, see
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/62068/

Change-Id: Ie03a9164a5f4e9b1aa5622eb44bbe891015a26be

commit_message:
Clean up fakeldap logging

The log strings in fakeldap were marked for translation and had
FakeLdap in each string. Let's save the translators' time and not
mark test strings for translation, and "fakeldap" is already in the
log message because of the formatter.

Change-Id: Ib1e4bf21ffb7a9e1d96c9465ebf0b00ae44881ee

(1 inline comment)

I haven't had a chance to fully review this yet, so please don't take this as comprehensive. That said, there's one thing that definitely needs addressing.

The way this patch stands, the backend servers are importing code from swift.proxy.controllers.base. Some packagers (Red Hat among them, I think) split Swift into different packages: one for the proxy, one for the object server, et cetera. Having a dependency from backend to proxy code goofs that up.

I'd recommend either putting that stuff in swift.common.utils / swift.common.request_helpers, or maybe just not having the get_sys_meta_prefix() function at all."}, {'account_id': 4108, 'date': '2013-11-04 15:25:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

@Alistair

First, I apologize for the many comments :) 

Some are style where there is never a right answer - still one can argue that one is better than other or that one style is better than many different styles in the same code/project.

Second, we need to change the DiskFile such that the object sysmeta would be persistent during a POST on an object - otherwise users would be able to eliminate sysmeta by simply doing a POST on an object.'}, {'account_id': 6198, 'date': '2013-11-06 20:20:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(1 inline comment)

What prevents a client from use x-account-sysmeta-* headers?

It would seem that we need a piece of middleware that is placed before all other middleware to filter out any client provided x-(account|container|object)-sysmeta-* header before sending it down the rest of the pipeline."}, {'account_id': 4108, 'date': '2013-11-08 11:41:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: (1 inline comment)

@Peter,

The idea here is that x-???-sysmeta is filtered at the proxy code - so a user can sent it, but it will be filtered out. 

If a middleware wishes to update the x-???-sysmeta, if does that using a function call that adds the metadata in an environment dictionary. Once the proxy filters all  x-???-sysmeta, it than adds the sysmeta stored in the environment dictionary (which we know was added by middleware). 

In this way we block users from changing sysmeta without the need for a piece of middleware at the front of the pipeline.'}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2013-11-08 14:36:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: (9 inline comments)

Thanks for comments, very helpful. I am working on next patch.

@Peter - as David says, inbound headers from client in x-*-sysmeta namespace are removed in proxy, prior to adding headers that middleware may have set. Additionally, outbound headers in this namespace are removed from responses, after they have been copied into the info dict for middleware to consume. So nothing in this namespace gets in/out unless middleware intervenes.'}, {'account_id': 6198, 'date': '2013-11-08 15:21:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: (1 inline comment)

@David:thanks for pointing out the subtly of that code. I completely missed that the headers were being nullified, effectively deleting them. This kind of subtly of the mechanism seems like it will lead to a supportability problem.

@David, @Alistair: it seems like this mechanism of using the environment is more than what is needed. If we had a simple piece of middleware that we ensured lived at the beginning of the pipeline, whose job is was to remove all incoming and all outgoing 'x-*-sysmeta-*' headers, then middleware can safely modify the existing headers without the need for the extra environment use.

Also, we could then use the same mechanism to ensure that all x-timestamps are completely filtered out as well."}, {'account_id': 4108, 'date': '2013-11-12 14:20:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: (3 inline comments)

@Peter, regarding using this technique vs. using a first mandatory middleware for filtering. 

Adding a mandatory middleware works, but it may be considered as changing the way Swift behaves today in the sense that core-swift is no longer a standalone deployable system. It may also be considered as less robust to configuration errors. 

I may be wrong, but my guess is that since the solution here conforms better to the way things were done so far, it is more likely to be accepted by the core team.'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2013-11-12 20:07:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

There's an efficiency argument to be made here.

If there's a sysmeta-stripper middleware at the front of the pipeline, then middleware can get sysmeta headers by reading them from the response; the middleware doesn't have to call some wacky function that goes around and makes a separate backend request but doesn't filter stuff out.

Let's say that some objects have "X-Object-Sysmeta-Quote: Futurama" set, and GET/HEAD responses for such objects should include a random Futurama quote in the X-Bender header.

In the world with a sysmeta stripper, the middleware makes the request as normal, inspects the response headers, and injects a quote into the response headers as appropriate. The proxy only had to make one HTTP request to one object server, same as always.

In the world without a sysmeta stripper, the middleware has to call get_object_info() to get the sysmeta headers (one request), and then call the app to get the object data (two requests). I don't like incurring the cost of extra HTTP requests if I can help it.


There's a similar argument in the header-setting case. Let's say I want to set "X-Object-Sysmeta-Plant: Ficus" for all ficus-like objects at PUT time.

In the world with a sysmeta stripper, my ficus middleware sets the header on the inbound response as appropriate, and it gets persisted to disk with the object, just like all the other metadata.

In the world without a sysmeta stripper, my ficus middleware has to do something else (what?) to set its metadata. Either that's a separate request, or it's some non-WSGI way of setting a header. One is inefficient, the other is confusing.'}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2013-11-13 17:39:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: (1 inline comment)

Thanks again for comments.

I'm not sure how best to proceed with this patch.

Re. from end stripper middleware - I agree with David that this would have to be a hardcoded, not in any way configurable.

It seems the main objection to my approach is that it is non-intuitive/confusing to pass sysmeta headers via a sub-dict of the environ, rather than as first class headers. (@Sam - I don't think there are any more requests involved either way)

So would the following be an acceptable compromise?

Inbound:

- middleware adds sysmeta headers to request headers set.

- by default, proxy will currently NOT pass these through for container and account requests, so...

- middleware instructs proxy to allow extra headers to pass through via a list of keys in the request environ.

- proxy reads this list and allows any specified sysmeta headers to pass through to backend (add to current pass_through_headers in base.py)

- we'd need to tighten up current object request behavior to block sysmeta by default.

- same mechanism could be used to block object x-timestamps unless middleware has specified that they should pass through.

Outbound:

- current proxy behavior would allow all sysmeta response headers to exit the proxy, so change this to remove sysmeta response headers by default.

- similar to inbound, middleware puts list of permitted outbound headers in the req environ, which proxy uses to allow only specified sysmeta response headers to pass out.

- if middleware has instructed proxy to pass through a response header, then the middleware is responsible for subsequently removing that header from the response if it should not be returned to client.

In summary, sysmeta passed in/out as req/resp headers , but only if middleware explicitly permits.

NB I am aware of other issues with this patch (e.g. obj POST handling) but would like to reach concensus on above if possible."}, {'account_id': 6198, 'date': '2013-11-14 03:12:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:
