First, I get test failures when running with pastedeploy 1.3.3, which is the minimum version in requirements.txt: http://paste.openstack.org/show/ftQ5104xsXkxxzQ4NShc/

Ubuntu 12.04 ships with python-pastedeploy 1.5.0, so updating the requirements.txt to 1.5.0 seems like it'd probably be okay (Fedora folks?).

Second, it seems sort of weird to me that this changeset will move things around in the pipeline. Once this lands, I plan on using it to make new middlewares and insert them in the pipeline, but I don't particularly want them to be moved to the front.

I worked up a quick patch to this patch that will leave things where they are in the pipeline if present. That way, my hypothetical future dlo middleware will get put in the pipeline if absent, but if a deployer wants to put it somewhere specific, they can.

Also, I don't like having the gatekeeper middleware first. In my ideal world, it'd be at index 1, and catch_errors would be at index 0. Having anything but catch_errors at index 0 creates the potential for stack traces to escape to clients.

The aforementioned patch: http://paste.openstack.org/show/VDQXId7HlCWQCWyfRJRv/"}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2013-12-09 21:54:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 14:

Also, I'm curious about the gatekeeper middleware's configurability. Are there use cases for both rejecting and ignoring requests with those headers set? IMHO, we'd be better off picking one behavior and just sticking with it instead of having Yet Another Configuration Option(tm).

My vote's for filtering out those headers. Seems like it's more consistent with the way extra headers are handled today, for example if I send X-Account-Meat-Stick header, it's just ignored, or if I send X-Account-Meta-Foo on a container request it's also ignored."}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2013-12-11 18:24:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 14:

@Sam thanks for comments. For this use case middleware (i.e. gatekeeper) needs to be forced to the start of the pipeline even if it is specified in another position in proxy_server.conf. It is still useful to allow those modules to be specified in conf file so that users can change their default config (e.g. log level) but the intent here is to enforce them being at start of pipeline.

I agree that catch_errors should be first and have now made that so. (was going to leave that to a follow up patch since its not strictly to do with sysmeta).

I think your anticipated middleware insertion use cases will be very easy to insert as they arise by adding something like your patch to the end of modify_wsgi_pipeline and I have added your mods to PipelineWrapper to support that. I'd suggest adding a required_other_filters list of middleware to be conditionally inserted as per your patch.

Also, I will remove the reject_bad_requests config option from gatekeeper."}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2013-12-11 18:30:34.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 15.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-12-11 19:51:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 15: Works for me

I like everything about this except the part where Swift pretends it's smarter than I am. :)

I really don't think that Swift should rearrange stuff in my pipeline. Add new stuff automatically? Heck yeah! Warn me if it thinks the pipeline is wrong? Sure, I like hints. Override my ordering regardless of what I really want? Nope; hands off, please.

PasteDeploy syntax is obscure (set X = Y, anyone?), confusing, and ugly, but it does give admins lots of power. I feel like taking that power away from admins just leaves us with an awful config file for no good reason.

That's all just my opinion, of course, so if two other folks really love this change enough to merge it, then I guess I'll just go listen to this http://www.amazon.com/dp/B002IYDTTK while Jenkins runs the tests."}, {'account_id': 6198, 'date': '2013-12-12 02:51:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 15:

Regardings @Sam's last post:

> I really don't think that Swift should rearrange stuff in my pipeline.

I completely agree with this statement. Swift should not read a configuration file, see how the pipeline is configured and then rearrange it in any way.

I am not sure how @Alistair feels about this, but to me, catch_errors and gatekeeper are not traditional middleware. They would not be specified in the pipeline, they would not have their own stand-alone configuration section and instead they should be considered part of the base WSGI server, where their options would be part of the WSGI's *-server configuration section.

In particular, I'd like to see catch_errors be part of all WSGI servers, while gatekeeper would only be part of the proxy-server.

> Add new stuff automatically? Heck yeah! Warn me if it thinks the pipeline is wrong? Sure, I like hints. Override my ordering regardless of what I really want? Nope; hands off, please.

Agree.

> PasteDeploy syntax is obscure (set X = Y, anyone?), confusing, and ugly, but it does give admins lots of power. I feel like taking that power away from admins just leaves us with an awful config file for no good reason.

I believe there is a good reason: we want to help make sure admins can't screw up their configuration. We need to make systems simple to setup, and giving them more rope to hang themselves can be very frustrating for the admin who is trying to untie the noose in the middle of a production fire-drill.

I agree that we could keep catch_errors as is, and just add gatekeeper as another piece of middleware that users have to read the documents to understand why it is highly recommended to come after catch_errors and before everything else in the pipeline. It feels like that it catering to the power user and not helping those who want simplicity to setup.

Today I don't know how many times I have pointed out to people why proxy-logging is needed twice in the pipeline, and where the right place to put it is and why. Very confusing and not simple. I believe our job as software engineers is to make systems that are simple to deploy and powerful in use.

> That's all just my opinion, of course, so if two other folks really love this change enough to merge it, then I guess I'll just go listen to this http://www.amazon.com/dp/B002IYDTTK while Jenkins runs the tests.

To me this discussion is really holding up this good work going forward.

So why don't we NOT force catch_errors and gatekeeper to the front of the pipeline and get this change in with just documentation, and then revisit the easy-of-use-or-don't-let-admins-hang-themselves discussion later?"}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2013-12-12 03:32:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 15:

> So why don't we NOT force catch_errors and gatekeeper to the front of the pipeline and get this change in with just documentation, and then revisit the easy-of-use-or-don't-let-admins-hang-themselves discussion later?

I can get behind that 100%."}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2013-12-12 16:27:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 15:

@Sam & @Peter I am also happy to retreat from forcing middleware to start of pipeline. 

However, I think it is important that the gatekeeper functionality is guaranteed to be in place somewhere between client and backend before we start persisting sysmeta. Otherwise, if people deploy this patch without configuring gatekeeper middleware, then we potentially start persisting sysmeta from clients that one day causes all sorts of problems.

So:
- gatekeeper SHOULD be ahead of any middleware that reads/writes sysmeta. Admins are responsible for getting that right in config.
- gatekeeper MUST be present somewhere. our responsibility to get that right.

How do you feel about this solution: 
- proxy inspects pipeline
- if gatekeeper is configured in pipeline, leave it where it is, safe in the knowledge that sysmeta is filtered (it may be that gatekeeper is not configured in the right place, but at least it is there)
- if gatekeeper is not configured in the pipeline, insert it at the END of pipeline immediately before the proxy server. This may not be the ideal place but it is safe - stuff may break (but that's because pipeline is misconfigured) but sysmeta will not leak in or out.
- (an equivalent solution would be 'if proxy does not find gatekeeper middleware in pipeline, then proxy performs filtering itself, to ensure security of sysmeta'. But inserting gatekeeper at end of pipeline achieves exactly the same, unless anyone sees a flaw)

If that's an acceptable approach for now, then we can subsequently revisit Peter's ideas to embed this functionality as non-middleware in wsgi."}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2013-12-12 17:30:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 15:

I could handle that.'}, {'account_id': 6198, 'date': '2013-12-12 17:40:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 15:

So how does an admin know which middleware writes sysmeta?

This seems like a recipe for confusion to leave this to the admins to know what we as developers barely know, as we don't know what third-party middleware does.

It certainly help float this work into the tree, which I think is more important at this point.

Ease of use is really important here."}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2013-12-12 19:03:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 15:

@Peter I guess any middleware using sysmeta needs to document that it requires gatekeeper to be ahead of it in pipeline.

I'm not pretending i think this solution is great. Its a compromise.

An alternative would be to revisit my original approach which required middleware to pass sysmeta via a sys_headers dict in environ (not req.headers, so no need for a gatekeeper - the gatekeeper thing arises from trying to use the same header dict for client stuff and sysmeta)

e.g. middleware uses something like put_sysmeta(req, k, v), get_sysmeta(resp, k) in request_helpers.py, functions which simply create/manage a sys_headers dict in the request environ. 

In fact, simpler, maybe we can instantiate a sys_headers dict in the environ during Request.__init__, so middleware just put/get sysmeta headers to req.sys_headers instead of req.headers (ditto for Response).

Proxy then takes care of first removing sysmeta from req.headers, then copying req.sys_headers into req.headers before generating backend requests. 

If folks feel that is now the better way to go then I'll do the unwinding, but I understand there were reservations about that approach before. 

It does mean the burden of 'getting it right' lies with middleware developer rather than admins.

Thoughts?"}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2013-12-12 19:17:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 15:

I think there's a couple things people are discussing here:

A: X-*-Sysmeta Shall Not Leak. Ever.

Automatically putting the gatekeeper middleware in the pipeline *anywhere* gives us this property.  Start, end, middle, randomly-chosen... it all stops leaks.

B: Middleware Can Use Sysmeta

For this, we need gatekeeper near the beginning; any middleware to the left of gatekeeper isn't invited to the sysmeta party.

C: Invalid Configs Should Be Repaired

For this, gatekeeper should be moved to the left if it's not far enough over already.


All that said, I think any patch that puts gatekeeper in the pipeline *somewhere* is acceptable at this point, as that gets us property A. We can fine-tune the rest later."}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2013-12-13 18:43:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 15:

I'm increasingly uncomfortable that I'm going to create an ongoing config headache/weirdness if this gatekeeper gets released into the wild and folks have to understand the subtlety of it being automatically inserted behind the scenes if they don't configure it themselves etc

So here's what I propose:  For the time being I will move the gatekeeper functionality into the proxy (its fairly trivial). That achieves the same as forcing gatekeeper to the end of the pipeline, at a fraction of the line count (no funky wsgi manipulation...). 

That addresses Sam's point A: the scope of this patch would be reduced to getting sysmeta persisted in the backends, enabling proxy code (like otherjon's) to send it, and making sure it never leaks in/out of the proxy.

A subsequent patch can address how middleware gets to read/write sysmeta, and if necessary introduce the gatekeeper to slide the filtering out of the proxy and up the pipeline. Personally, I'd like to avoid the gatekeeper approach altogether, but that becomes a subsequent debate for a subsequent patch...

I'm not aware of anyone else right now depending on this patch for *middleware* setting sysmeta ??

I've been tied up with other stuff today but will hopefully get another patch up by Monday."}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2013-12-16 16:54:05.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 16.'}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2013-12-16 16:58:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 16:

Change in this patch is that as promised all the gatekeeper middleware and wsgi manipulation stuff is gone: sysmeta header filtering is done very early in the proxy server. This should satisfy otherjon's needs.

WSGI manipulation stuff seems to have already been reincarnated here https://review.openstack.org/#/c/62090/6 - as and when that is done we can reconsider gatekeeper middleware to enable middleware to also set sysmeta."}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2013-12-16 17:32:03.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 17.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-12-16 18:57:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 17: Works for me

(8 inline comments)

If catch_errors is in the pipeline, then we wind up with a pipeline like "gatekeeper catch_errors ... proxy", and the first two are backwards there. However, if catch_errors is also absent, then we get "catch_errors gatekeeper ... proxy", which is what we want.

Dang. I'll try to work up a patch for this tonight, but that's a blocker IMO.

If I manually add X-Container-Sysmeta-Color: red to a container (request directly to the container server), then the container server *does* put it in a HEAD response, but the proxy *does not* pass it through to the client. Good.

If I downgrade to master, the container server does not put X-Container-Sysmeta-Color in HEAD responses, so downgrading won't cause a sysmeta leak. Good.

Seems weird to me that the container server checks headers for meta-ness on GET/HEAD, but the account server just spews out whatever it has. That's not really about this patch; I stumbled on it when I wondered why the container server had 4 call sites for is_sys_or_user_meta while the account server only had 2. This is more a note for other reviewers than it is anything else.

Personally, I don't particularly care for the add_sys_meta function for one reason: it has no callers. It's not a blocker for me, but I wouldn't be at all sad if it went away.

Also, there's some inline comments here and there.

To summarize:

* 99% working. Hooray!

* Must fix placement of gatekeeper in pipeline

* Nice to fix test stuff noted in inline comments, esp. debugging print

* Not a fan of add_sys_meta, but if you really like it, I'll live with it'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2014-01-07 02:54:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 19:

[{'created': '2013-10-11 14:38:58.000000000', 'message': 'Store x-container-attr-* headers in container db.

This is one of a set of patches implementing a container-forwarding feature.
(see https://blueprints.launchpad.net/swift/+spec/cluster-federation)

Container forwarding middleware needs to store per-container state
such as a pointer to another cluster to which the container is forwarded.
This patch adds a reserved namespace x-container-attr-* for request
headers (added to a request by middleware) that will be stored in the
container db, and returned as response headers, in a similar way to user
defined metadata.

Change-Id: I80b8b14243cc59505f8c584920f8f527646b5f45
'}, {'created': '2013-11-22 18:56:35.000000000', 'message': 'Generic means for persisting system metadata.

Middleware or core features may need to store metadata
against accounts, containers or objects. For example,
container forwarding middleware stores a per-container
pointer to another cluster to which the container is
forwarded.

This patch adds a generic mechanism for system metadata
to be persisted in backend databases, without polluting
the user metadata namespace, by using the reserved
header namespace x-<server_type>-sysmeta-*.

Modifications are firstly that backend servers persist
system metadata headers alongside user metadata and
other system state.

For accounts and containers, system metadata in PUT and
POST requests is treated in the same way as user
metadata. For objects, system metadata is persisted for
PUT requests only. POSTs (including POST as a copy) do
not modify or delete existing system metadata.

Secondly, changes in the proxy controllers ensure that
headers in the system metadata namespace will pass through
in requests to backend servers. A convenience function
(swift.common.request_helpers.add_sys_meta) is provided
for middleware to add system metadata to a request, and
as a heads-up to developers that the reserved namespace
exists.

Thirdly, system metadata returned from backend servers
in GET or HEAD responses is added to the info_cache
dict, which middleware can access.

Finally, a gatekeeper middleware module is provided
which filters all system metadata headers from requests
and responses. This middleware should be placed close to
start of the proxy wsgi pipeline, ahead of any middleware
that may wish to set system metadata headers. This
prevents clients from writing or reading system metadata.

It is intended that the gatekeeper middleware will be
enforced at the start of the proxy pipeline in the same
way as planned for catch_errors middleware.

Middleware or core features may need to store metadata
against accounts or containers. For example,
container forwarding middleware stores a per-container

This patch adds a generic mechanism for system metadata

in GET or HEAD responses is added to the cached info

and responses by removing headers with names starting
x-account-sysmeta-, x-container-sysmeta-. The gatekeeper
also removes headers starting x-object-sysmeta- in
anticipation of future support for system metadata being

included in the wsgi pipeline. Specifically, the proxy
server forces catch_errors middleware to the start of the

the gatekeeper is positioned ahead of any middleware
that may wish to set system metadata headers. This
prevents clients from writing or reading system metadata.

For accounts and containers, system metadata in PUT
and POST requests is treated in a similar way to user
metadata. System metadata is not yet supported for
object requests.

Secondly, changes in the proxy controllers ensure that
headers in the system metadata namespace will pass through
in requests to backend servers.

Thirdly, system metadata returned from backend servers
in GET or HEAD responses is added to the cached info

which filters all system metadata headers from requests
and responses by removing headers with names starting

also removes headers starting x-object-sysmeta- in

commit_message:
Generic means for persisting system metadata.

Middleware or core features may need to store metadata
against accounts or containers. This patch adds a
generic mechanism for system metadata to be persisted
in backend databases, without polluting the user
metadata namespace, by using the reserved header
namespace x-<server_type>-sysmeta-*.

Modifications are firstly that backend servers persist
system metadata headers alongside user metadata and
other system state.

For accounts and containers, system metadata in PUT
and POST requests is treated in a similar way to user
metadata. System metadata is not yet supported for
object requests.

Secondly, changes in the proxy controllers ensure that
headers in the system metadata namespace will pass through
in requests to backend servers.

Thirdly, system metadata returned from backend servers
in GET or HEAD responses is added to the cached info
dict, which middleware can access.

Finally, a gatekeeper middleware module is provided
which filters all system metadata headers from requests
and responses by removing headers with names starting
x-account-sysmeta-, x-container-sysmeta-. The gatekeeper
also removes headers starting x-object-sysmeta- in
anticipation of future support for system metadata being
set for objects. This prevents clients from writing or
reading system metadata.

The required_filters list in swift/proxy/server.py is
modified to include the gatekeeper middleware so that
if the gatekeeper has not been configured in the
pipeline then it will be automatically inserted close
to the start of the pipeline.

blueprint cluster-federation

Change-Id: I80b8b14243cc59505f8c584920f8f527646b5f45

Are you saying that they are polished - - that we've made them minimal? I don't think thats the case, is it?"}, {'account_id': 360, 'date': '2013-12-18 01:47:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

lifeless: I think we still have quite a bit of work to do. But marking config files as unpolished seems unnecessary (it sort of demotivates me to want to fix them). And besides many of these referred to the wrong Git repo anyway so I figured both should change.

To me these config files are what they are... hopefully getting better. No need to have comments that tell us how far along that process we are.'}, {'account_id': 8449, 'date': '2013-12-18 07:33:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: (2 inline comments)

imo the edited link to the git repo is a good fix - don't feel strongly either way wrt to the 'not polished' disclaimer so no score"}, {'account_id': 6449, 'date': '2013-12-18 10:31:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I tend to think here that we should avoid being assertive in the header, because whatever we assert will usually be wrong.

Perhaps something like:

"This file was taken from upstream $PROJECT and may need to be updated to match upstream changes in default/available configuration options. Please submit patches at: blah blah"

I think it's unhelpful to assert a binary state of polishedness, when some level of polishing has been done and a potentially unknown amount of work is required to achieve a fully polished state.
However, I think it's also a bad idea to entirely remove the nod towards upstream. We are going to have users be bitten by these files getting stale, eventually.'}, {'account_id': 360, 'date': '2013-12-18 13:21:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Chris: As far as I'm concerned the nod to upstream is implied here is doesn't just cover these templates... it covers the entire set of the TripleO elements. I'm happy to add back in that verbage however, although in general I do think the less we say in these template headers the better."}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-12-18 19:58:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

So the point of this was that they were a literal *copy* of upstream. Since them some of them *have* been fixed: they have been audited, default settings removed, and what remains is intentional.

I'd love to see that work progress, and I don't want to lose the metadata that tells us which ones have had that done to them."}, {'account_id': 1247, 'date': '2013-12-19 06:53:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

"metadata" like this belongs in a bug report or something

A disclaimer like this has a tendency to linger forever - as Chris said, "polished" vs "unpolished" is not a binary state - what event is likely to trigger someone else proposing to remove the disclaimer?'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-12-27 06:03:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Abandoned

Lets not say unpolished...

Updates the disclaimer at the top of many of our config files
so it is a bit more consise (avoiding the use of unpolished).

at http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/tripleo-image-elements/.

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-01-09 11:30:46.000000000', 'message': 'Remove redundant meter (name,type,unit) tuples from Resource model

Fixes bug 1267162

Previously, a list of meter (name,type,unit) tuples with per-sample
cardinality was added to the Resource model by the storage driver
get_resource method.

However this potential huge and highly repetitive list was then
promptly discarded by the API layer, as the meter links in the API
Resource representation are populated via subsequent calls into
the storage driver get_meters method.

Now, we avoid the scaling issue by suppressing the creation of
this unused meter list.

Change-Id: I18dee7552836c724798ea1340e2e933c09d8a294
'}]
commit_message:
Remove redundant meter (name,type,unit) tuples from Resource model

Fixes bug 1267162

Previously, a list of meter (name,type,unit) tuples with per-sample
cardinality was added to the Resource model by the storage driver
get_resource method.

However this potential huge and highly repetitive list was then
promptly discarded by the API layer, as the meter links in the API
Resource representation are populated via subsequent calls into
the storage driver get_meters method.

Now, we avoid the scaling issue by suppressing the creation of
this unused meter list.

Change-Id: I18dee7552836c724798ea1340e2e933c09d8a294

commit_message:
Remove deprecated hp3par_domain option

The hp3par_domain config option was deprecated in the Havana release.
This just removes it from the config reference guide for the Icehouse
release. This patch resolves the documentation change for patch that
removed it from the source code and unit tests, see
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/65114/ for details.

Change-Id: I8187a772974f36c7ebd5f5674c5c9e0bc1c3376b

commit_message:
Use constants for the execution event strings

Since these will be used in the future, add a
comment saying this, as well as switch to using
executor level constants instead of local strings
for these events.

[{'created': '2013-12-20 05:10:40.000000000', 'message': "Various optimizations to RingBuilder.rebalance()

Overall gain is about 20-22% of time on my laptop. This includes:

* replacing string sort_key with a tuple (because we can and because
  compairing two 3-tuples is faster than comparing two 26-byte strings);
* keeping track of hungriest dev in tier (allows us to use built-in
  dict.__getitem__ as a key instead of lambdas in couple of places);
* remove unnecessary sorted() call in the innermost loop (because we
  don't need to sort all of them or better we don't need to sort
  anything there);
* memoize tiers for each dev (saves just a couple of percents but why
  not).

Performance measurments have been done using this script:
http://paste.openstack.org/show/55609/

Related-Bug: #1262166
Related-Bug: #1261659

commit_message:
Various optimizations to RingBuilder.rebalance()

Overall gain is about 20-22% of time on my laptop. This includes:

* replacing string sort_key with a tuple (because we can and because
  compairing two 3-tuples is faster than comparing two 26-byte strings);
* keeping track of hungriest dev in tier (allows us to use built-in
  dict.__getitem__ as a key instead of lambdas in couple of places);
* remove unnecessary sorted() call in the innermost loop (because we
  don't need to sort all of them or better we don't need to sort
  anything there);
* memoize tiers for each dev (saves just a couple of percents but why
  not).

Performance measurments have been done using this script:
http://paste.openstack.org/show/55609/

Related-Bug: #1262166
Related-Bug: #1261659
Change-Id: If38bd9fe82efc12b01e9aa146e0f4ab565fb6bea

commit_message:
Restart openvswitch-switch after installation

This minor change restarts openvswitch-switch after installation
as the openvswitch kernel module may not be present when that service
gets installed/started.  In that situation, subsequent ovs-vsctl
commands will hang.

Change-Id: Idb1c2442e313707ced70f0792f6cc22c5fc7ef39
Closes-Bug: 1267528

commit_message:
Initial rubocop support for recipes.

Per the mailing list thread, introducing Rubocop as a replacement for Tailor.
Assuming Jenkins likes this, more pedantic patches will follow to make Rubocop
happy. So far this is just spacing issues and adding UTF-8 headers, but more
work will need to be done to remove all of the changes for the .rubocop-todo.yml

Change-Id: I590ac5ec03ce6a00dd73027d6798e36105a32af1

commit_message:
Clean up documentation of common elements

When DIB_COMMON_ELEMENTS was added, some of the documentation no
longer made sense where it was.  This moves the documentation of
the common elements to the spot where DIB_COMMON_ELEMENTS is
defined.

Change-Id: Icd4a3eddcf95726989527f56075dde99f2ae5ca7

commit_message:
port nova v2 images related tests into nova v3 part1

This changeset only copies the v2 files into the appropriate v3
directories unchanged. This is being tried in order to make
reviewing of the porting easier as gerrit will display only what
is actually changed for v3 rather than entirely new files.

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api-tests

Change-Id: I4355adee713bb217da7f12d4c2fe9b8abf015b05

commit_message:
Cleanup from business logic refactor

This patchset resolves a few minor nits including proper translation
of a couple strings in exceptions, order of addCleanup in
test_keystoneclient, a simple white-space change to make a line
more readable, and adding a bug reference to a comment.  All of these
changes are in response to comments on the deletion business logic
refactor that moved business logic from the controllers to the *_api
managers.

Change-Id: I2a446611a0fb91b946e986342ae5ede926b8dd44
bp: assignment-controller-first-class

commit_message:
Update the descriptions for the log cfg opts

The existing logging config descriptions are incorrect.

This fix makes the documented config settings for verbose/debug
match their current behaviour.

Change-Id: I1a3830ca616c379cd37593fb3c3ef30a0d368cd9
Closes-Bug: #1261793

[{'created': '2014-01-02 21:17:37.000000000', 'message': "Refactoring the loadbalancing view classes

In several view classes, there's overloaded functions that do nothing but
calling the overloaded function and returning the results. Removed theses
functions.

Change-Id: I595b978fb7e9da867bd7a4d66dd07e9eaec9e7b4
Closes-Bug: #1265619

commit_message:
Refactoring the loadbalancing view classes

In several view classes, there's overloaded functions that do nothing but
calling the overloaded function and returning the results. Removed theses
functions.

Change-Id: I595b978fb7e9da867bd7a4d66dd07e9eaec9e7b4
Closes-Bug: #1265619

'}, {'created': '2013-12-10 21:48:46.000000000', 'message': 'Raise diskfile.py module coverage to > 98%

We attempt to get the code coverage (with branch coverage) to 100%,
but fall short because due to interactions between coverage.py and
CPython's peephole optimizer. See:

    https://bitbucket.org/ned/coveragepy/issue/198/continue-marked-as-not-covered

In the main diskfile module, we remove the check for a valid
"self._tmppath" since it is only one of a number of fields that could
be verified and it was not worth trying to get coverage for it. We
also remove the try / except around the close() method call in the
DiskFileReader's app_iter_ranges() method since it will never be
called in a context that will raise a quarantine exception (by
definition ranges can't generate a quarantine event).

We also:

* fix where quarantine messages are checked to ensure the
  generator is actually executed before the check
* in new and modified tests:
  * use assertTrue in place of assert_
  * use assertEqual in place of assertEquals
* fix references to the reserved word "object"

Change-Id: I6379be04adfc5012cb0b91748fb3ba3f11200b48

commit_message:
Raise diskfile.py module coverage to > 98%

We attempt to get the code coverage (with branch coverage) to 100%,
but fall short because due to interactions between coverage.py and
CPython's peephole optimizer. See:

    https://bitbucket.org/ned/coveragepy/issue/198/continue-marked-as-not-covered

In the main diskfile module, we remove the check for a valid
"self._tmppath" since it is only one of a number of fields that could
be verified and it was not worth trying to get coverage for it. We
also remove the try / except around the close() method call in the
DiskFileReader's app_iter_ranges() method since it will never be
called in a context that will raise a quarantine exception (by
definition ranges can't generate a quarantine event).

We also:

* fix where quarantine messages are checked to ensure the
  generator is actually executed before the check
* in new and modified tests:
  * use assertTrue in place of assert_
  * use assertEqual in place of assertEquals
* fix references to the reserved word "object"

Change-Id: I6379be04adfc5012cb0b91748fb3ba3f11200b48

commit_message:
Let drivers override default rebuild() behaviour

The rebuild compute method currently makes separate calls to destroy()
and spawn(), but this introduces race conditions with drivers where
another compute process could claim the VM resources between destroy
and spawn. This is a particular problem for baremetal where the
planned ephemeral preservation feature requires that the rebuild
happen on the same physical node.

Partial-Bug: #1174154
blueprint: baremetal-preserve-ephemeral
Co-Authored-By: Robert Collins <rbtcollins@hp.com>
Co-Authored-By: Joe Gordon <joe.gordon0@gmail.com>

Change-Id: I5fadc27207ed5725ecf0cf6bc34a52a95af42679

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-11-14 09:49:17.000000000', 'message': "Using host mount info for datastore selection

Currently the VMDK driver picks a datastore for volume creation based
on space utilization. The shadow VM corresponding to the volume is
migrated to a different host and datastore if the volume is attached
to an instance created in a host which cannot access the volume's
current datastore. To reduce these migrations, this fix selects a
datastore which is connected to maximum number of hosts, provided
there is enough space to accommodate the volume. Ties are broken
based on space utilization; datastore with low space utilization
is preferred.

Testing done:
Hosts:
h1, h2, h3

Datastores:
h1 [local_ds_1, iscsi1, nfs1]
h2 [local_ds_2, iscsi1, nfs1]
h3 [local_ds_3, iscsi1]

* instance vm1 in h1 with disk in iscsi1
* attach vol1 to vm1 creates the vmdk in iscsi1
* remove iscsi1 from h3
* space_utilization_nfs1 = 0.04, space_utilization_iscsi1 = 0.06
* atatch vol2 to vm1 creates the vmdk in nfs1

Change-Id: I5ecf22d782857fca0889799229465c49afe188a0
Closes-Bug: #1250816
backport: havana

commit_message:
VMDK:Using host mount info for datastore selection

Currently the VMDK driver picks a datastore for volume creation based
on space utilization. The shadow VM corresponding to the volume is
migrated to a different host and datastore if the volume is attached
to an instance created in a host which cannot access the volume's
current datastore. To reduce these migrations, this fix selects a
datastore which is connected to maximum number of hosts, provided
there is enough space to accommodate the volume. Ties are broken
based on space utilization; datastore with low space utilization
is preferred.

Closes-Bug: #1250816
Change-Id: I5ecf22d782857fca0889799229465c49afe188a0

commit_message:
Add envs for different sqlalchemy versions

Adjust tests to skip the sqlalchemy test if
sqlalchemy is not installed. Adjust examples
to fallback to a directory based backend if
the sqlalchemy does not load or is not available.

Include a updated tox.ini (generated from the
toxgen.py script) that includes the new venv
variations.

Change-Id: I7686f09901a9b65d7c81b4e037b5bffc24aa7ef7

Which problem?'}, {'account_id': 8443, 'date': '2014-01-10 06:53:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Logical problem. If you merge this before fixing tests with keystone gate will be broken. If you try to merge tests before then there is a question in test what do they test and will they work after changing this parameter.
So there is no reason to have a separate commit for this change as this is a trivial change which can and should be a part of a patch which solves a problem with gate. Otherwise we will constantly fight with failing gate due to non atomic changes and interdependencies between patches.'}, {'account_id': 8334, 'date': '2014-01-10 06:56:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Reorganise compute config reference

This patch
* Removes content that is covered by installation (adding group,
   fixing file permissions, multiple compute nodes)
* Removes empty section (hypervisors)
* Merges duplicate content (overview/explanation of nova.conf)
* Flattens section structure, and removes "post-install config"
   section label that was a legacy of previous structure
* Addresses outdated reference to Xen configuration info.

Closes-bug: 1095095
Change-Id: I8922606fe38d30d5ac6288901a866c635c686fbe

commit_message:
Fix os.getlogin() problem with no tty
Catch OSError(s) from  os.getlogin() and fall back to looking at
environment variables to figure out the user's name. The OSError
is thrown where there is no tty for the python process when
os.getlogin() is called.

Fixes LP: 1221491

Change-Id: I440a583ff82ca5ddde1983cc36634c3599a0750b

commit_message:
Remove deprecated squid directives from devtest

The cache_object protocol has been removed from squid in the version in
Ubuntu 13.10 causing our example config to fail to start.

Change-Id: I4429a79acc9992797f7d81ee16edcdbc7d7c808e

commit_message:
Make neutron element preserve state

Neutron does not keep much state but it is useful to keep the keystone
signing files around, otherwise tokens have to be signed again.

Change-Id: I6664cf2f3717df3f44239e14dd8bece63afa8d24

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-12-14 12:02:42.000000000', 'message': 'Allow customized reseller_prefix in Ceilometer middleware for Swift

Swift can be configured to use a different reseller prefix than AUTH_.
In this case Ceilometer returns None as resource_id.

This patch allows to set the reseller prefix, with a fallback to
AUTH_ if not set. An additionally test to verify this was added.

Change-Id: I1ba40091582da46c0385a71d1828bb3820a5e2b5
Closes-Bug: #1260965

commit_message:
Allow customized reseller_prefix in Ceilometer middleware for Swift

Swift can be configured to use a different reseller prefix than AUTH_.
In this case Ceilometer returns None as resource_id.

This patch allows to set the reseller prefix, with a fallback to AUTH_
if not set. It also ensures that the reseller prefix ends with ``_``.
Two additional tests to verify this were added.

Change-Id: I1ba40091582da46c0385a71d1828bb3820a5e2b5
Closes-Bug: #1260965

[{'created': '2014-01-08 10:00:36.000000000', 'message': "Avoid false negatives on message signature comparison

Fixes bug 1262255

Previously, samples for the 'instance.scheduled' meter were always
rejected with a false negative on the message signature verification.

The problem occured because certain resource metadata (such as the
block_device_mapping) in the 'scheduler.run_instance.scheduled'
notification are realized as a list of dict, and are thus similarly
encoded in the corresponding sample payload.

However the message signature computation then became indeterminate,
as the unicode representation of equivalent dicts is not guaranteed
equal (e.g. depends on insertion order in the case of hash collisions).

Now, we avoid false negatives by explicitly re-ordering insertion
into such dicts.

Change-Id: I77f7d89229518cf040608d7eb3307e2257bce07a
(cherry picked from commit e9cde137b0c24ac755bbb3629b9a831391574f6c)
"}]
commit_message:
Avoid false negatives on message signature comparison

Fixes bug 1262255

Previously, samples for the 'instance.scheduled' meter were always
rejected with a false negative on the message signature verification.

The problem occured because certain resource metadata (such as the
block_device_mapping) in the 'scheduler.run_instance.scheduled'
notification are realized as a list of dict, and are thus similarly
encoded in the corresponding sample payload.

However the message signature computation then became indeterminate,
as the unicode representation of equivalent dicts is not guaranteed
equal (e.g. depends on insertion order in the case of hash collisions).

Now, we avoid false negatives by explicitly re-ordering insertion
into such dicts.

Change-Id: I77f7d89229518cf040608d7eb3307e2257bce07a
(cherry picked from commit e9cde137b0c24ac755bbb3629b9a831391574f6c)

commit_message:
Removes vim configuration headers

 - Removes vim headers: It's not needed to set tabstop tons of times,
   this can be done by setting vimrc.
 - I did not update files in common/* and install_venv_common.py because
   these files are sync with oslo.

Note:
  http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2013-October/017353.html

Closes-Bug: #1265474
Change-Id: Ia09dc2c908187a756bf55eaba74655484304517d

afazekas, thank you for the review.

According to the hacking rules all source files should contain the header: http://docs.openstack.org/developer/hacking/#openstack-licensing

The decorator is designed to suppress only specific kinds of exceptions. I need that for testing cases when exceptions might happen but that's a normal behaviour.

There are patches to devstack-gate and devstack which will enable Ironic tests in tempest as soon as they are merged: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/53899/ https://review.openstack.org/#/c/56345/"}, {'account_id': 7711, 'date': '2013-11-21 11:49:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

service and some tests for the Ironic API.

commit_message:
API tests for Ironic

Ironic is a baremetal provisioning service that
is intended to replace nova-baremetal-driver.

Recently it was integrated to devstack so now
it's reasonable to start testing it with tempest.

This patch adds a client for baremetal
provisioning service and some tests for the Ironic API.

Change-Id: Ifd65d6a60179e72dbfa81825f234f0ff76ebb055

commit_message:
Use Resource() class from common Oslo code

In the process of unification of the clients code we should
reuse common functionality from Oslo. Resource() class from ceilometer
duplicates Oslo funclionality, so we replace it with inheritance

Change-Id: I4e4b83252cdc87e8484d15e351cd5dab08f3ed8a

commit_message:
Using floating-ip-{associate|disassociate}

This patch implements a blueprint to add more consistency into
nova command, especially for the subcommand "floating-ip-*"

Currently when we want to associate or disassociate an ip with
nova we have to use add-floating-ip and remove-floating-ip. This
is not consitent with the actual scheme of the subcommands:

example:
  nova image-*
  nova flavor-*
  nova floating-ip-*

 + In the client v1.1 this patch displays a deprecated message when printing
   the help message for add-floating-ip and remove-floating-ip.
 + In the client v3 this patch do nothing because all floating ip commands are being
   removed.

$:~/python-novaclient$ nova help | grep floating
    add-floating-ip     DEPRECATED, use floating-ip-associate instead.
    floating-ip-associate
                        Associate a floating IP address to a server.
    floating-ip-bulk-create
                        Bulk create floating ips by range.
    floating-ip-bulk-delete
                        Bulk delete floating ips by range.
    floating-ip-bulk-list
                        List all floating ips.
    floating-ip-create  Allocate a floating IP for the current tenant.
    floating-ip-delete  De-allocate a floating IP.
    floating-ip-disassociate
                        Remove a floating IP address from a server.
    floating-ip-list    List floating ips for this tenant.
    floating-ip-pool-list
                        List all floating ip pools.
    remove-floating-ip  DEPRECATED, use floating-ip-disassociate instead.

Implements: blueprint commands-floating-ip
Change-Id: I5337d0f1ce5ec4826da6ecd2b6ae4ae7b97801e0

commit_message:
Tolerate deleted trust on stack delete

Currently if a trust has already been deleted, the stack delete
fails and the stack becomes undeletable, so instead catch the
NotFound exception on trust delete, as there's nothing to do.

Change-Id: I1346cefdf6c5f2dea2bc9e2fdd4b9e7b14d60c31
Closes-Bug: #1266434

Update the hard-coded default template for the LoadBalancer
resource, so it uses an image called F20-x86_64-cfntools

commit_message:
Update Loadbalancer default template to F20 image

Update the hard-coded default template for the LoadBalancer
resource, so it uses an image called F20-x86_64-cfntools

The Fedora cloud images now contain heat-cfntools, and I've
tested with Fedora-x86_64-20-20131211.1-sda.qcow2, downloaded
from http://fedoraproject.org/en/get-fedora#clouds and it works.

You can download this image direct to glance by doing:

glance image-create --name F20-x86_64-cfntools --disk-format qcow2 \
     --container-format bare --is-public true --copy-from \
     http://cloud.fedoraproject.org/fedora-20.x86_64.qcow2

For users of other distros, you can now override the default
template by copying the built-in template and specifying whatever
image or LB configuration you wish, see
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/64874/

Change-Id: I95e0451b03118a75be0a25f512304649eae42356
Closes-Bug: #1234375

The sheepdog driver fails when trying to
create volume from image due to a bug in
SheepdogDriver.copy_image_to_volume.

The utils.convert method is being passed the
tempfile object, but should only be passed

Closes-Bug: 1261941

commit_message:
Fix sheepdog copy_image_to_volume method

The sheepdog driver fails when trying to
create volume from image due to a bug in
SheepdogDriver.copy_image_to_volume.

The utils.convert method is being passed the
tempfile object, but should only be passed
the name of the tempfile.

Change-Id: I6b261d29895bf9c2c30b2d95d74e5be58b8e9b10
Closes-Bug: 1261941

commit_message:
1st & last sample timestamps in Resource representation

Fixes bug 1262335

Previously, the first and last sample timestamps associated
with a resource were calculated by the storage driver, but
then discarded.

Now, we include these values in the API resource representation.

Change-Id: I3cf6081e1ac1294083f6326f85dabebab0d02203
(cherry picked from commit 6a9dc97f962c288f5037d59d05a771823eb4bcdd)

Hi,

I don't want to do a +1 or a -1, just a warning here.

I'd be very careful with this, because installing the python-libvirt package makes the nova unit tests fail (which is why nova should build-conflict with python-libvirt). This is due to the fact that Nova uses its own emulation of a fake libvirt python package if it doesn't see one installed.

So I'm not sure if this has a consequence with what I just wrote above."}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2014-01-10 06:03:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned

commit_message:
Add libvirt-python in prep for using pypi libvirt

Libvirt is now consumable via pypi. Add this as a requirement so that
nova can consume it in this way rather than relying on system packages.
Note that this will require newer C libvirt than is currently available
on the precise slaves. Will need working cloud archive before this can
go in.

Change-Id: I1bb37d121b8488d0d751d7f95e914e75427492b8

(1 inline comment)

A number of bits of trailing whitespace.

This will affect execution speed in some circumstances - more thrashing == less throughput == slower - but lets do it and observe - we may be sufficiently isolated from actual IO to have it not matter. More worrisome to me is that this will raise the concurrent resources used in the gate - block device, network etc - and that may trigger failures.

Lastly, should this perhaps be done in tempest itself, changing the default used? That way other people running tempest will see the same behaviour."}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2013-11-29 22:25:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

conceptually I want this is.

However, trailing whitespace needs to be cleaned up. Additionally we should factor this into a single variable that's used for all the jobs, so when something changes, we aren't updating it 6 times.

I also think that setting this in d-g is the right place, as we believe right now that we have the resources to handle 8 way in the gate, which is a statement of our understanding of the gate (and the use of things like micro instances), and doesn't apply to the tempest general case."}, {'account_id': 5196, 'date': '2013-12-02 14:57:00.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-12-02 15:41:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Doesn't seem to work

commit_message:
Up the default concurrency on tempest runs

This changes the default testr concurrency to 8 for tempest runs. This
will not affect the execution speed of tempest, but because there are
more workers it might shake loose more race conditions. Additionally,
this commit adds a new env variable to devstack gate to set the
concurrency, TEMPEST_CONCURRENCY.

Change-Id: I6963488e183af03ee14e5d5b7f116518493e3ec2
